 Asia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Zamboanga del Norte]]\n[[Category:Languages of Zamboanga del Sur]]\n[[Category:Languages of Zamboanga Sibugay]]\n[[Category:Languages of Basilan]]\n[[Category:Languages of Sulu]]\n[[Category:Languages of Tawi-Tawi]]\n[[Category:Culture of Zamboanga City]]\n[[Category:Culture of Cavite]]\n[[Category:False friends]]\n", "name_user": "Juanmakabulos", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chavacano"}
{"title_page": "Cyclone Herold", "text_new": "{{for|other cyclones named Harold or Herold|List of cyclones named Harold}}\n{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Name = Tropical Cyclone Herold\n| Type = cyclone\n| Year = 2020\n| Basin = SWI\n| Image location = Herold 2020-03-17 0610Z.jpg\n| Image name = Herold at peak intensity on 17 March\n| Image alt = Herold at peak intensity on 17 March\n| Formed = {{start date|12 March}} 2020\n| Dissipated = {{end date|20 March}} 2020\n| 1-min winds = 100\n| 10-min winds = 95\n| Pressure = 957\n| Damages = None\n| Fatalities = 5 total\n| Areas = [[Madagascar]], [[Tromelin Island]], [[Mauritius]], [[Rodrigues]]\n| Hurricane season = [[2019\u201320 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season]]\n}}\n\n'''Intense Tropical Cyclone Herold''' was the first major tropical cyclone [[Tropical cyclones in 2020|worldwide in 2020]]. Herold was the tenth zone of disturbed weather, ninth depression, eighth moderate tropical storm, sixth severe tropical storm, fifth [[tropical cyclone]], and second intense tropical cyclone of the slightly above-average [[2019\u201320 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season]]. Herold formed on 13 March from a disorganized area of low pressure near [[Tromelin Island]].<ref name=6t>[[http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITF_202003011000.pdf]]</ref>\n\n==Meteorological history==\n[[File:Herold 2020 track.png|left|thumb|Map plotting the intensity and track of the storm, according to the [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale]]]]\nEarly in March 2020, an area of low pressure existed near [[Tromelin Island]], but it dissipated on 4 March. It unexpectedly regenerated the next day near the Mascarene Islands. M\u00e9t\u00e9o France predicted it would strengthen into a tropical depression by the end of the week.<ref name=6t>[[http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITF_202003011000.pdf]]</ref> Over the next two weeks, it gradually gained convection,<ref>[http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITF_202003061045.pdf%7C \"Low Pressure Area forms near Tromelin Islands\"]</ref> until on 13 March, Zone of Disturbed Weather 10 [[Tropical cyclogenesis|formed]] northwest of [[Madagascar]]. The next day, the JTWC and MFR upgraded it to a tropical depression.<ref>https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/tropical-cyclone-herold-forms-coast-madagascar-200314085617745.html</ref> Late on 14 March, 10 reached moderate tropical storm intensity and was named ''Herold''. Herold began to undergo slow intensification. At 18:00 UTC on 15 March, the cyclone was designated [[Tropical Cyclone]] Herold. Late on March 17, Herold reached its peak intensity as an intense tropical cyclone, and the JTWC classified it as a [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale#Category 3|Category 3-equivalent tropical cyclone]]. As this happened, Herold rapidly moved southeast,<ref>https://phys.org/news/2020-03-nasa-tropical-cyclone-herold-eye.html</ref> Herold's peak intensity was short-lived. On 18 March, Herold began rapidly weakening. Later that day, Herold became extratropical. Finally, on 20 March, Herold dissipated entirely.<ref>https://blogs.nasa.gov/hurricanes/tag/herold-2020/</ref>\n\n==Preparations==\n===Madagascar===\nThe first alert, a green alert (issued two to five days before the storm's potential impact<ref name=Meteo>http://www.meteomadagascar.mg/cyclone</ref>), was issued on March 13 by M\u00e9t\u00e9o Madagascar for the areas in northeastern Madagascar.<ref>https://www.gdacs.org/report.aspx?eventtype=TC&eventid=1000660</ref> The next day, the alert was upgraded to a yellow alert (issued one to two days before storm, storm is going to be damaging area but it has not truly happened yet<ref name=Meteo>http://www.meteomadagascar.mg/cyclone</ref>). \n===Mauritius and Rodrigues===\nOn 18 March, a class four cyclone warning was issued for [[Rodrigues]].<ref>https://reliefweb.int/report/madagascar/madagascarmauritius-cyclone-herold-flash-update-no-1-17-march-2020</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n===Madagascar===\nHeavy rain was recorded in northeastern Madagascar on 13 March, which impacted more than 3,203 people.<ref>17 March 2020. [https://lexpress.mg/17/03/2020/sava-et-analanjirofo-plus-de-trois-mille-sinistres-de-herold/|\"Herold drenches Madagascar\".] Retrieved 24 March 2020.</ref> 95 mm (3.7 inches) fell on [[Sambava]] that same day. Intense flooding occurred in the Ankavanana River, which threatened more than 1000 people. Four people were killed in the [[Sava Region]]. Flooding impacted more than 100 schools. Homes were swept away in areas near [[Maroantsetra]].<ref name=TopNews>16 March 2020. [https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/Tropical-Cyclone-Herold-drenches-northeastern-Madagascar/7671584383092/|\"Top News: Tropical Cyclone Herold drenches northeastern Madagascar\"] Retrieved 24 March 2020.</ref> Near the Andranofotsy River, people were most affected. By 17 March, though, the water level had decreased a fair amount in the community.<ref>17 March 2020. [https://lexpress.mg/17/03/2020/sava-et-analanjirofo-plus-de-trois-mille-sinistres-de-herold/|\"Sava and Analanjirofo - Over three thousand victims of Herold\"] Retrieved 25 March 2020.</ref><ref name=Herold>16 March 2020. [https://lexpress.mg/16/03/2020/intemperies-une-personne-emportee-par-la-crue-a-maroantsetra/|\"Herold floods Maroantsetra\"] Retrieved 25 March 2020.</ref> One of the 5 deaths caused by Cyclone Herold was of a 36-year-old man. On March 15, he had just put his herd of oxen in a safe place when he suddenly disappeared in Mahalevona. Around 6 p.m. that day, his body was found. That day, the water level on land rose to 2 meters (6 feet). 13 of 20 municipalities in the [[Maroantsetra]] district were underwater and 28 houses had been destroyed in the town of Mahalevona.<ref name=Herold></ref> In Maroantsetra, 104 homes were affected by the [[storm surge]]. A school in Anjanazana was found with puddles of mud in its classrooms.<ref>17 March 2020. [https://lexpress.mg/17/03/2020/sava-et-analanjirofo-plus-de-trois-mille-sinistres-de-herold/%7C \"Cyclone Herold in Madagascar\"]. Retrieved 27 March 2020.</ref> The effects of Herold didn't end until the [[Tropical cyclone watches and warnings|cyclone alerts]] were lifted on 17 March for the entire island.<ref>17 March 2020.[https://www.newsmada.com/2020/03/17/precipitations-des-pluies-attendues-a-antananarivo/|\"Precipitation: Rains expected in Antananarivo\"] Retrieved 27 March 2020.</ref> In total, 4,771 people in Madagascar were victims of Herold. 911 homes were flooded. 178 huts were damaged, and 127 residencies were destroyed in Madagascar.<ref>22 March 2020. [http://www.lagazette-dgi.com/?p=40732|\"Damage assessment: 4,771 victims after the passage of Herold\"] Retrieved 27 March 2020.</ref> An update on 18 March confirmed another death and 1 person missing. 4,315 people were impacted by Herold in Maroantsetra alone. Also in Maroantsetra, 79 classrooms were damaged, and 24 were damaged in [[Sainte-Marie]].<ref>20 March 2020.[https://www.newsmada.com/2020/03/20/cyclone-herold-bilan-provisoire-cinq-morts-et-un-disparu/|\"Cyclone Herold: provisional assessment: Five dead and 1 missing\"] Retrieved 27 March 2020.</ref>\n\n===Mauritius and Rodrigues===\nWhen Herold passed in between the islands of [[Mauritius]] and [[Rodrigues]] on 17 March, it made schools close and caused eighty people to seek refuge in accommodation centers. In the islands, damage was mainly minimal. In most areas, it was limited to downed trees and power outages. However, a gust of 130 km/h (81 mph) was recorded in [[Sir Ga\u00ebtan Duval Airport]]. Maximum rainfall was no more than 29 mm (1.1 inches).<ref name=TopNews></ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n* [[Tropical cyclones in 2020]]\n* [[Cyclone Belna]], a storm of similar intensity that also affected Madagascar\n* [[2019\u201320 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season]]\n[[Category:Intense Tropical Cyclones]]\n[[Category:Cyclones in Madagascar]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|other storms of the same name|List of cyclones named Herold}}\n{{distinguish|Cyclone Harold}}\n{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Name = Tropical Cyclone Herold\n| Type = cyclone\n| Year = 2020\n| Basin = SWI\n| Image location = Herold 2020-03-17 0610Z.jpg\n| Image name = Herold at peak intensity on 17 March\n| Image alt = Herold at peak intensity on 17 March\n| Formed = {{start date|12 March}} 2020\n| Dissipated = {{end date|20 March}} 2020\n| 1-min winds = 100\n| 10-min winds = 95\n| Pressure = 957\n| Damages = None\n| Fatalities = 5 total\n| Areas = [[Madagascar]], [[Tromelin Island]], [[Mauritius]], [[Rodrigues]]\n| Hurricane season = [[2019\u201320 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season]]\n}}\n\n'''Intense Tropical Cyclone Herold''' was the first major tropical cyclone [[Tropical cyclones in 2020|worldwide in 2020]]. Herold was the tenth zone of disturbed weather, ninth depression, eighth moderate tropical storm, sixth severe tropical storm, fifth [[tropical cyclone]], and second intense tropical cyclone of the slightly above-average [[2019\u201320 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season]]. Herold formed on 13 March from a disorganized area of low pressure near [[Tromelin Island]].<ref name=6t>[[http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITF_202003011000.pdf]]</ref>\n\n==Meteorological history==\n[[File:Herold 2020 track.png|left|thumb|Map plotting the intensity and track of the storm, according to the [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale]]]]\nEarly in March 2020, an area of low pressure existed near [[Tromelin Island]], but it dissipated on 4 March. It unexpectedly regenerated the next day near the Mascarene Islands. M\u00e9t\u00e9o France predicted it would strengthen into a tropical depression by the end of the week.<ref name=6t>[[http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITF_202003011000.pdf]]</ref> Over the next two weeks, it gradually gained convection,<ref>[http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITF_202003061045.pdf%7C \"Low Pressure Area forms near Tromelin Islands\"]</ref> until on 13 March, Zone of Disturbed Weather 10 [[Tropical cyclogenesis|formed]] northwest of [[Madagascar]]. The next day, the JTWC and MFR upgraded it to a tropical depression.<ref>https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/tropical-cyclone-herold-forms-coast-madagascar-200314085617745.html</ref> Late on 14 March, 10 reached moderate tropical storm intensity and was named ''Herold''. Herold began to undergo slow intensification. At 18:00 UTC on 15 March, the cyclone was designated [[Tropical Cyclone]] Herold. Late on March 17, Herold reached its peak intensity as an intense tropical cyclone, and the JTWC classified it as a [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale#Category 3|Category 3-equivalent tropical cyclone]]. As this happened, Herold rapidly moved southeast,<ref>https://phys.org/news/2020-03-nasa-tropical-cyclone-herold-eye.html</ref> Herold's peak intensity was short-lived. On 18 March, Herold began rapidly weakening. Later that day, Herold became extratropical. Finally, on 20 March, Herold dissipated entirely.<ref>https://blogs.nasa.gov/hurricanes/tag/herold-2020/</ref>\n\n==Preparations==\n===Madagascar===\nThe first alert, a green alert (issued two to five days before the storm's potential impact<ref name=Meteo>http://www.meteomadagascar.mg/cyclone</ref>), was issued on March 13 by M\u00e9t\u00e9o Madagascar for the areas in northeastern Madagascar.<ref>https://www.gdacs.org/report.aspx?eventtype=TC&eventid=1000660</ref> The next day, the alert was upgraded to a yellow alert (issued one to two days before storm, storm is going to be damaging area but it has not truly happened yet<ref name=Meteo>http://www.meteomadagascar.mg/cyclone</ref>). \n===Mauritius and Rodrigues===\nOn 18 March, a class four cyclone warning was issued for [[Rodrigues]].<ref>https://reliefweb.int/report/madagascar/madagascarmauritius-cyclone-herold-flash-update-no-1-17-march-2020</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n===Madagascar===\nHeavy rain was recorded in northeastern Madagascar on 13 March, which impacted more than 3,203 people.<ref>17 March 2020. [https://lexpress.mg/17/03/2020/sava-et-analanjirofo-plus-de-trois-mille-sinistres-de-herold/|\"Herold drenches Madagascar\".] Retrieved 24 March 2020.</ref> 95 mm (3.7 inches) fell on [[Sambava]] that same day. Intense flooding occurred in the Ankavanana River, which threatened more than 1000 people. Four people were killed in the [[Sava Region]]. Flooding impacted more than 100 schools. Homes were swept away in areas near [[Maroantsetra]].<ref name=TopNews>16 March 2020. [https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/Tropical-Cyclone-Herold-drenches-northeastern-Madagascar/7671584383092/|\"Top News: Tropical Cyclone Herold drenches northeastern Madagascar\"] Retrieved 24 March 2020.</ref> Near the Andranofotsy River, people were most affected. By 17 March, though, the water level had decreased a fair amount in the community.<ref>17 March 2020. [https://lexpress.mg/17/03/2020/sava-et-analanjirofo-plus-de-trois-mille-sinistres-de-herold/|\"Sava and Analanjirofo - Over three thousand victims of Herold\"] Retrieved 25 March 2020.</ref><ref name=Herold>16 March 2020. [https://lexpress.mg/16/03/2020/intemperies-une-personne-emportee-par-la-crue-a-maroantsetra/|\"Herold floods Maroantsetra\"] Retrieved 25 March 2020.</ref> One of the 5 deaths caused by Cyclone Herold was of a 36-year-old man. On March 15, he had just put his herd of oxen in a safe place when he suddenly disappeared in Mahalevona. Around 6 p.m. that day, his body was found. That day, the water level on land rose to 2 meters (6 feet). 13 of 20 municipalities in the [[Maroantsetra]] district were underwater and 28 houses had been destroyed in the town of Mahalevona.<ref name=Herold></ref> In Maroantsetra, 104 homes were affected by the [[storm surge]]. A school in Anjanazana was found with puddles of mud in its classrooms.<ref>17 March 2020. [https://lexpress.mg/17/03/2020/sava-et-analanjirofo-plus-de-trois-mille-sinistres-de-herold/%7C \"Cyclone Herold in Madagascar\"]. Retrieved 27 March 2020.</ref> The effects of Herold didn't end until the [[Tropical cyclone watches and warnings|cyclone alerts]] were lifted on 17 March for the entire island.<ref>17 March 2020.[https://www.newsmada.com/2020/03/17/precipitations-des-pluies-attendues-a-antananarivo/|\"Precipitation: Rains expected in Antananarivo\"] Retrieved 27 March 2020.</ref> In total, 4,771 people in Madagascar were victims of Herold. 911 homes were flooded. 178 huts were damaged, and 127 residencies were destroyed in Madagascar.<ref>22 March 2020. [http://www.lagazette-dgi.com/?p=40732|\"Damage assessment: 4,771 victims after the passage of Herold\"] Retrieved 27 March 2020.</ref> An update on 18 March confirmed another death and 1 person missing. 4,315 people were impacted by Herold in Maroantsetra alone. Also in Maroantsetra, 79 classrooms were damaged, and 24 were damaged in [[Sainte-Marie]].<ref>20 March 2020.[https://www.newsmada.com/2020/03/20/cyclone-herold-bilan-provisoire-cinq-morts-et-un-disparu/|\"Cyclone Herold: provisional assessment: Five dead and 1 missing\"] Retrieved 27 March 2020.</ref>\n\n===Mauritius and Rodrigues===\nWhen Herold passed in between the islands of [[Mauritius]] and [[Rodrigues]] on 17 March, it made schools close and caused eighty people to seek refuge in accommodation centers. In the islands, damage was mainly minimal. In most areas, it was limited to downed trees and power outages. However, a gust of 130 km/h (81 mph) was recorded in [[Sir Ga\u00ebtan Duval Airport]]. Maximum rainfall was no more than 29 mm (1.1 inches).<ref name=TopNews></ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n* [[Tropical cyclones in 2020]]\n* [[Cyclone Belna]], a storm of similar intensity that also affected Madagascar\n* [[2019\u201320 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season]]\n[[Category:Intense Tropical Cyclones]]\n[[Category:Cyclones in Madagascar]]\n", "name_user": "Jason Rees", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclone_Herold"}
{"title_page": "I'll Be Seeing You (song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name      = I'll Be Seeing You\n| cover     =\n| alt       =\n| type      =\n| written   =\n| published = 1938 by Marlo Music Corporation\n| writer    =\n| composer  = [[Sammy Fain]]\n| lyricist  = [[Irving Kahal]]\n}}\n\"'''I'll Be Seeing You'''\" is a [[popular music|popular]] song about [[nostalgia]], with music by [[Sammy Fain]] and lyrics by [[Irving Kahal]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Leonard|first1=Hal|title=I'll Be Seeing You: 51 Songs of World War II|date=January 1, 1995|publisher=Hal Leonard Corp.|isbn=978-0793537617|page=47}}</ref> Published in 1938, it was inserted into the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[Right This Way]]'', which closed after fifteen performances.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Leonard|first1=Hal|title=I'll Be Seeing You: 51 Songs of World War II|date=January 1, 1995|publisher=Hal Leonard Corp.|isbn=978-0793537617|page=12}}</ref> The title of the 1944 film ''[[I'll Be Seeing You (1944 film)|I'll Be Seeing You]]'' was taken from this song at the suggestion of the film's producer, [[Dore Schary]]. The song is included in the film's soundtrack. The earliest recording of the song was by [[Dick Todd (singer)|Dick Todd]] in 1940 on the [[Bluebird Records|Bluebird]] label.<ref name=\"Archive 2018-08-21\">{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/78_ill-be-seeing-you_dick-todd-irving-kahal-sammy-fain_gbia0061812a |title=I'll Be Seeing You by Dick Todd |publisher=[[Internet Archive]] |date=2018-08-21 |accessdate=2020-04-21 |quote=Digitized at 78 revolutions per minute. Four stylii were used to transfer this record. }}</ref>\n\nThe resemblance between the main tune's first four lines and a passage within the theme of the last movement of [[Gustav Mahler]]'s [[Symphony No. 3 (Mahler)|Third Symphony]] (1896) was pointed out by [[Deryck Cooke]] in 1970.<ref>Cooke's radio broadcast is described in [[Hans Keller]], 'Truth & Music', ''Music and Musicians Magazine'', November 1970</ref>  Mahler may have derived this passage from the overture to Daniel Auber's comic opera (Marco Spada (1852).  \n\n[[Billie Holiday]]'s 1944 recording of the song was the final transmission sent by [[NASA]] to the ''[[Opportunity (rover)|Opportunity]]'' rover on [[Mars]] when its mission ended on 13 February 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/02/opportunity-did-not-answer-nasas-final-call-and-its-now-gone-to-us/ |title=Opportunity did not answer NASA\u2019s final call, and it\u2019s now lost to us |publisher=Ars Technica |date=February 13, 2019 |author=Berger, Eric}}</ref>\n\n==Chart appearances==\nThe recording by [[Bing Crosby]] became a hit in 1944, reaching number one for the week of July 1.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954|date=1986|publisher=Record Research Inc|location=Wisconsin, USA|isbn=0-89820-083-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/109 109]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/109}}</ref> [[Frank Sinatra]]'s version with [[Tommy Dorsey and His Orchestra]] from 1940 charted in 1944 and peaked at No. 4.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954|date=1986|publisher=Record Research Inc|location=Wisconsin, USA|isbn=0-89820-083-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/138 138]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/138}}</ref> A recording by [[the Poni-Tails]] reached number 87 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] for the week ending November 16, 1959.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/poni-tails/chart-history/hot-100/song/576618|title=Poni-Tails I'll Be Seeing You Chart History|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other Notable Recordings==\n* [[Eric Clapton]] recorded the song as the final track on his 2016 album [[I Still Do]], which except for his Christmas LP [[Happy Xmas (album)|\nHappy Xmas]] was his final album. \"I love the song and I love the sentiment,\" he said in a [[Chicago Tribune]] interview. \"Just in case I don't cut another record, . . . I kind of might be saying goodbye.\"<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune 2016-05-17\">{{cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-eric-clapton-new-album-i-still-do-20160517-story.html |title=Eric Clapton 'kind of might be saying goodbye' |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |publisher=[[Tribune Publishing]] |date=2016-05-17 |accessdate=2020-04-10 |quote=I love the song and I love the sentiment. Just in case I don't cut another record, . . . I kind of might be saying goodbye. }}</ref>\n* [[Linda Ronstadt]] made it the final track on her studio album [[Hummin' to Myself (Linda Ronstadt album)|Hummin' to Myself.]]<ref name=\"AllMusic Ronstadt Seeing You\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/hummin-to-myself-mw0000301888 |title=Linda Ronstadt - Hummin to Myself |last=Latham |first=Aaron |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=2020-04-10 |quote=Track 11 - I'll Be Seeing You }}</ref>\n* [[Ray Charles]] performed the song on his 1967 album [[Ray Charles Invites You to Listen]].<ref name=\"SecondHandSongs 2020-04-21\">{{cite web |url=https://secondhandsongs.com/performance/283910 |title=Original Versions Ill Be Seeing You Ray Charles |work=SecondHandSongs |accessdate=2020-04-21 }}</ref>\n* [[Willie Nelson]] included it on his 1994 studio album [[Healing Hands of Time]].<ref name=\"Allmusic Nelson Healing Hands\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-hands-of-time-mw0000122070 |title=Willie Nelson - Healing Hands of Time |last=Monkman |first=Martin |work=ALLMUSIC Review |accessdate=2020-04-10 |quote=Track 9 - I'll Be Seeing You }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|billie-holiday|ill-be-seeing-you}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Billie Holiday}}\n{{Bing Crosby}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:I'll Be Seeing You (Song)}}\n[[Category:Songs about nostalgia]]\n[[Category:1938 songs]]\n[[Category:1959 singles]]\n[[Category:Pop standards]]\n[[Category:Torch songs]]\n[[Category:Songs from musicals]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Sammy Fain]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Irving Kahal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name      = I'll Be Seeing You\n| cover     =\n| alt       =\n| type      =\n| written   =\n| published = 1938 by Marlo Music Corporation\n| writer    =\n| composer  = [[Sammy Fain]]\n| lyricist  = [[Irving Kahal]]\n}}\n\"'''I'll Be Seeing You'''\" is a [[popular music|popular]] song about [[nostalgia]], with music by [[Sammy Fain]] and lyrics by [[Irving Kahal]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Leonard|first1=Hal|title=I'll Be Seeing You: 51 Songs of World War II|date=January 1, 1995|publisher=Hal Leonard Corp.|isbn=978-0793537617|page=47}}</ref> Published in 1938, it was inserted into the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[Right This Way]]'', which closed after fifteen performances.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Leonard|first1=Hal|title=I'll Be Seeing You: 51 Songs of World War II|date=January 1, 1995|publisher=Hal Leonard Corp.|isbn=978-0793537617|page=12}}</ref> The title of the 1944 film ''[[I'll Be Seeing You (1944 film)|I'll Be Seeing You]]'' was taken from this song at the suggestion of the film's producer, [[Dore Schary]]. The song is included in the film's soundtrack. The earliest recording of the song was by [[Dick Todd (singer)|Dick Todd]] in 1940 on the [[Bluebird Records|Bluebird]] label.<ref name=\"Archive 2018-08-21\">{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/78_ill-be-seeing-you_dick-todd-irving-kahal-sammy-fain_gbia0061812a |title=audioI'll Be Seeing You by Dick Todd |publisher=[[Internet Archive]] |date=2018-08-21 |accessdate=2020-04-21 |quote=Digitized at 78 revolutions per minute. Four stylii were used to transfer this record. }}</ref>\n\nThe resemblance between the main tune's first four lines and a passage within the theme of the last movement of [[Gustav Mahler]]'s [[Symphony No. 3 (Mahler)|Third Symphony]] (1896) was pointed out by [[Deryck Cooke]] in 1970.<ref>Cooke's radio broadcast is described in [[Hans Keller]], 'Truth & Music', ''Music and Musicians Magazine'', November 1970</ref>  Mahler may have derived this passage from the overture to Daniel Auber's comic opera (Marco Spada (1852).  \n\n[[Billie Holiday]]'s 1944 recording of the song was the final transmission sent by [[NASA]] to the ''[[Opportunity (rover)|Opportunity]]'' rover on [[Mars]] when its mission ended on 13 February 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/02/opportunity-did-not-answer-nasas-final-call-and-its-now-gone-to-us/ |title=Opportunity did not answer NASA\u2019s final call, and it\u2019s now lost to us |publisher=Ars Technica |date=February 13, 2019 |author=Berger, Eric}}</ref>\n\n==Chart appearances==\nThe recording by [[Bing Crosby]] became a hit in 1944, reaching number one for the week of July 1.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954|date=1986|publisher=Record Research Inc|location=Wisconsin, USA|isbn=0-89820-083-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/109 109]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/109}}</ref> [[Frank Sinatra]]'s version with [[Tommy Dorsey and His Orchestra]] from 1940 charted in 1944 and peaked at No. 4.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954|date=1986|publisher=Record Research Inc|location=Wisconsin, USA|isbn=0-89820-083-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/138 138]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/138}}</ref> A recording by [[the Poni-Tails]] reached number 87 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] for the week ending November 16, 1959.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/poni-tails/chart-history/hot-100/song/576618|title=Poni-Tails I'll Be Seeing You Chart History|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other Notable Recordings==\n* [[Eric Clapton]] recorded the song as the final track on his 2016 album [[I Still Do]], which except for his Christmas LP [[Happy Xmas (album)|\nHappy Xmas]] was his final album. \"I love the song and I love the sentiment,\" he said in a [[Chicago Tribune]] interview. \"Just in case I don't cut another record, . . . I kind of might be saying goodbye.\"<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune 2016-05-17\">{{cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-eric-clapton-new-album-i-still-do-20160517-story.html |title=Eric Clapton 'kind of might be saying goodbye' |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |publisher=[[Tribune Publishing]] |date=2016-05-17 |accessdate=2020-04-10 |quote=I love the song and I love the sentiment. Just in case I don't cut another record, . . . I kind of might be saying goodbye. }}</ref>\n* [[Linda Ronstadt]] made it the final track on her studio album [[Hummin' to Myself (Linda Ronstadt album)|Hummin' to Myself.]]<ref name=\"AllMusic Ronstadt Seeing You\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/hummin-to-myself-mw0000301888 |title=Linda Ronstadt - Hummin to Myself |last=Latham |first=Aaron |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=2020-04-10 |quote=Track 11 - I'll Be Seeing You }}</ref>\n* [[Ray Charles]] performed the song on his 1967 album [[Ray Charles Invites You to Listen]].<ref name=\"SecondHandSongs 2020-04-21\">{{cite web |url=https://secondhandsongs.com/performance/283910 |title=Original Versions Ill Be Seeing You Ray Charles |work=SecondHandSongs |accessdate=2020-04-21 }}</ref>\n* [[Willie Nelson]] included it on his 1994 studio album [[Healing Hands of Time]].<ref name=\"Allmusic Nelson Healing Hands\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-hands-of-time-mw0000122070 |title=Willie Nelson - Healing Hands of Time |last=Monkman |first=Martin |work=ALLMUSIC Review |accessdate=2020-04-10 |quote=Track 9 - I'll Be Seeing You }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|billie-holiday|ill-be-seeing-you}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Billie Holiday}}\n{{Bing Crosby}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:I'll Be Seeing You (Song)}}\n[[Category:Songs about nostalgia]]\n[[Category:1938 songs]]\n[[Category:1959 singles]]\n[[Category:Pop standards]]\n[[Category:Torch songs]]\n[[Category:Songs from musicals]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Sammy Fain]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Irving Kahal]]\n", "name_user": "RStephenK", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor edit to note", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I%27ll_Be_Seeing_You_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Noah Lawson", "text_new": "{{short description|Fictional character from the Australian Channel Seven soap opera Home and Away}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox soap character | series = Home and Away\n| name = Noah Lawson\n| image = Noah_Lawson.png\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption = Beau Brady as Noah Lawson\n| portrayer = [[Beau Brady]]\n| creator =\n| years = 2000\u20132004\n| first = 6 September 2000\n| last = 26 November 2004\n| classification = [[List of past Home and Away characters#L|Former, regular]]\n| occupation = Student at Summer Bay High (2000\u201301)<br>Counsellor (2001\u201304)\n| mother = [[Jill Lawson]]\n| brothers =[[Jude Lawson]]\n| books = ''Home and Away:The Long Goodbye''\n| spinoffs=''[[Home and Away: Secrets and the City]]'' (2002)\n| wife = [[Hayley Smith (Home and Away)|Hayley Smith]] (2004)\n}}\n\n'''Noah Lawson''' is a [[character (arts)|fictional character]] from the Australian [[Seven Network|Channel Seven]] [[soap opera]] ''[[Home and Away]]'', played by [[Beau Brady]]. The character debuted on-screen during the episode airing on 6 September 2000.\n\n==Characterization==\nJacqueline Maley writing for ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' refers to Noah as a \"bad boy\" type character.<ref name=badboy>{{cite web|last=Maley|first=Jacqueline|title=Bec's Beau tells why they split|url=http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/people/becs-beau-tells-why-they-split-20101004-164ev.html?|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=([[Fairfax Media]])|accessdate=2011-02-21|date=5 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Storylines==\n\n===Backstory===\nNoah suffered a troubled childhood when his father left his mother, Jill ([[Tracy Mann]]) to raise him and his elder brother [[Jude Lawson|Jude]] ([[Ben Steel]]) alone. Jill's religious over-zealousness drove Jude away as they grew and as a result, she became protective of Noah. One night, Jill's attempt in order to protect Noah from \"The Devil\" by lighting candles went awry when Noah's sheets caught alight. Jill was subsequently institutionalized and Noah went to live with Jude.\n\n===2000\u201304===\nNoah is first seen when he saves [[Hayley Lawson|Hayley Smith]] ([[Bec Cartwright]]) from a gang of thugs at a nightclub by offering her a ride on his motorcycle. After an initially shaky start, Noah and Hayley begin dating and after both fail Year 12, they repeat together the following year. Their relationship is seemingly steady until Noah kisses Skye Patterson ([[Angela Keep]]) at Hayley's 18th birthday party. As a result of their breakup, Noah descends into alcoholism but with the help of [[Flynn Saunders]] ([[Martin Dingle-Wall]]), he is able to begin a \"controlled drinking\" therapy. Noah and Hayley reconcile but this is tested when Jill arrives on the scene and wants to rebuild their relationship. Noah isn't keen at first and worries when Jill manages to influence Hayley after learning that her father [[Ken Smith (Home and Away)|Ken]] (Anthony Phelan) had died the previous year. Jude, Noah and [[Irene Roberts (Home and Away)|Irene Roberts]] ([[Lynne McGranger]]), Hayley's foster mother worry about the amount of time Hayley is spending with Jill. After talking to a local minister, Jill finally agrees to get some further psychiatric help and Noah and Jude forgive her.\n\nAfter completing his HSC, Noah becomes a counsellor at the Drop-in Centre along with Flynn, [[Gypsy Nash]] ([[Kimberley Cooper]]), [[Shelley Sutherland]] ([[Paula Forrest]]). Noah and Hayley move into an apartment, dubbed \"The Palace\" along with [[Dani Sutherland]] ([[Tammin Sursok]]) and [[Josh West (Home and Away)|Josh West]] ([[Daniel Collopy]]). Noah and Hayley split the following year after Hayley kisses Josh and they begin seeing other people. [[Kit Hunter]] ([[Amy Mizzi]]) shows a romantic interest in Noah after he helps with her alcoholism but he rebuffs her.\n\nNoah and Hayley reunite after Hayley loses her memory in a car crash with [[Brodie Hanson]] ([[Susie Rugg]]). Hayley soon regains her memory and is devastated when she remembers [[Alex Poulos]] ([[Danny Raco]]), who she had been dating prior to the accident, has left her for Brodie. On the night of Hayley's 21st birthday, Noah proposes and she accepts. Hayley's suggestion of inviting Jill and having a church wedding does not sit well with Noah. In the end the couple marry in an outdoor ceremony along with [[Kane Phillips|Kane]] ([[Sam Atwell]]) and [[Kirsty Phillips]] ([[Christie Hayes]]), who are renewing their vows.\n\nWhen Sarah Lewis (Luisa Hastings-Edge) begins terrorizing Summer Bay wanting retribution for the death of her boyfriend, Felix Walters ([[Josh Lawson]]), she storms [[Leah Patterson-Baker|Leah Patterson]]'s ([[Ada Nicodemou]]) house where a number of Bay residents have gathered and she demands Felix's killer steps forward. Noah tries to explain that Sarah was the one who killed Felix by injecting him with [[Crystal Meth]]. After Sarah knocks Detective Peter Baker ([[Nicholas Bishop]]) unconscious, she goes after Dani who arrives at the house, Noah follows Sarah and is shot dead in the process.\nSarah then turns the gun on herself and commits suicide. Following his death, Noah appears in many of Hayley's visions during the grieving process and makes one final appearance during the 2004 Season finale. In the Surf Club, a bar is built in Noah's memory named after him and a painting of him by Hayley remains on the wall for a number of years.\n\n==Reception==\nFor his portrayal of Noah, Brady was nominated for the \"Most Popular New Male Talent\" Logie in 2001.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=age&kw=tammin+sursok+and+home+and+away&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=ILL010403GIEKS1S8FQA|title=Lisa McCune still Logies darling|date=3 April 2001|work=[[Illawarra Mercury]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|page=5|accessdate=13 May 2013}}</ref> He was also nominated for the Silver Logie for \"Most Popular Actor\" for three years in a row from 2003 to 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?multiview=true&sy=nstore&page=1&kw=Beau+Brady&pb=all_ffx&dt=enterRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=article&rc=200&rm=200&sp=adv&clsPage=1&hids=&sids=SAG0305118J4DC34BHDE|title=Heeler loses Faith in Gold|first=Suzanne|last=Carbonne|work=[[Sunday Age]]|date=11 May 2003|accessdate=13 May 2013|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?multiview=true&sy=nstore&page=1&kw=Beau+Brady&pb=all_ffx&dt=enterRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=article&rc=200&rm=200&sp=adv&clsPage=1&hids=&sids=ILL0403237MBVV4MTMRU|date=23 March 2004|accessdate=13 May 2013|work= The Ilawarra Mercury|title=The Logie motions|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?multiview=true&sy=nstore&page=1&kw=Beau+Brady&pb=all_ffx&dt=enterRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=article&rc=200&rm=200&sp=adv&clsPage=1&hids=&sids=SHD050501VV5J01H53KG|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|date=1 May 2005|accessdate=13 May 2013|title=TV& Radio|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|first=Rachel|last=Browne}}</ref> The episode featuring Noah's funeral won writer Louise Crane-Bowes an [[Australian Writers Guild]] award in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awg.com.au/images/awgie%20winners%201968-2006.pdf|title=Winners 1968-2006|publisher=[[Australian Writers Guild]]|accessdate=24 July 2012|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029150956/http://www.awg.com.au/images/awgie%20winners%201968-2006.pdf|archive-date=29 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The episode featuring Noah's appearance as a ghost to say goodbye to Hayley also earned a nomination in this category in the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australiantelevision.net/awards/awgie2005.html|title=australian television information archive -AWGIE awards 2005}}</ref>\n\n[[Mark Juddery]] of ''[[The Sun-Herald]]'' described Noah's death at the hands of Sarah Lewis as the \"Biggest Event\" in the series' history in his article about television characters being killed off in order to boost ratings.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?multiview=true&sy=nstore&page=1&kw=Beau+Brady&pb=all_ffx&dt=enterRange&dr=1month&so=relevance&sf=article&rc=200&rm=200&sp=adv&clsPage=1&hids=&sids=SHD050306106JD4EB37L|title=\nDeath by popular vote|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|first=Mark|last=Judderry|date=6 March 2005|accessdate=13 May 2013|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Home and Away characters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lawson, Noah}}\n[[Category:Home and Away characters]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2000]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional murdered people in soap operas]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fictional character from the Australian Channel Seven soap opera Home and Away}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox soap character | series = Home and Away\n| name = Noah Lawson\n| image = Noah_Lawson.png\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption = Beau Brady as Noah Lawson\n| portrayer = [[Beau Brady]]\n| creator =\n| years = 2000\u20132004\n| first = 6 September 2000\n| last = 26 November 2004\n| classification = [[List of past Home and Away characters#L|Former, regular]]\n| occupation = Student at Summer Bay High (2000\u201301)<br>Counsellor (2001\u201304)\n| mother = [[Jill Lawson]]\n| brothers =[[Jude Lawson]]\n| books = ''Home and Away:The Long Goodbye''\n| spinoffs=''[[Home and Away: Secrets and the City]]'' (2002)\n| wife = [[Hayley Smith (Home and Away)|Hayley Smith]] (2004)\n}}\n\n'''Noah Lawson''' is a [[character (arts)|fictional character]] from the Australian [[Seven Network|Channel Seven]] [[soap opera]] ''[[Home and Away]]'', played by [[Beau Brady]]. The character debuted on-screen during the episode airing on 6 September 2000.\n\n==Characterization==\nJacqueline Maley writing for ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' refers to Noah as a \"bad boy\" type character.<ref name=badboy>{{cite web|last=Maley|first=Jacqueline|title=Bec's Beau tells why they split|url=http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/people/becs-beau-tells-why-they-split-20101004-164ev.html?|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=([[Fairfax Media]])|accessdate=2011-02-21|date=5 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Storylines==\n\n===Backstory===\nNoah suffered a troubled childhood when his father left his mother, Jill ([[Tracy Mann]]) to raise him and his elder brother [[Jude Lawson|Jude]] ([[Ben Steel]]) alone. Jill's religious over-zealousness drove Jude away as they grew and as a result, she became protective of Noah. One night, Jill's attempt in order to protect Noah from \"The Devil\" by lighting candles went awry when Noah's sheets caught alight. Jill was subsequently institutionalized and Noah went to live with Jude.\n\n===2000\u201304===\nNoah is first seen when he saves [[Hayley Lawson|Hayley Smith]] ([[Bec Cartwright]]) from a gang of thugs at a nightclub by offering her a ride on his motorcycle. After an initially shaky start, Noah and Hayley begin dating and after both fail Year 12, they repeat together the following year. Their relationship is seemingly steady until Noah kisses Skye Patterson ([[Angela Keep]]) at Hayley's 18th birthday party. As a result of their breakup, Noah descends into alcoholism but with the help of [[Flynn Saunders]] ([[Martin Dingle-Wall]]), he is able to begin a \"controlled drinking\" therapy. Noah and Hayley reconcile but this is tested when Jill arrives on the scene and wants to rebuild their relationship. Noah isn't keen at first and worries when Jill manages to influence Hayley after learning that her father [[Ken Smith (Home and Away)|Ken]] (Anthony Phelan) had died the previous year. Jude, Noah and [[Irene Roberts (Home and Away)|Irene Roberts]] ([[Lynne McGranger]]), Hayley's foster mother worry about the amount of time Hayley is spending with Jill. After talking to a local minister, Jill finally agrees to get some further psychiatric help and Noah and Jude forgive her.\n\nAfter completing his HSC, Noah becomes a counsellor at the Drop-in Centre along with Flynn, [[Gypsy Nash]] ([[Kimberley Cooper]]), [[Shelley Sutherland]] ([[Paula Forrest]]). Noah and Hayley move into an apartment, dubbed \"The Palace\" along with [[Dani Sutherland]] ([[Tammin Sursok]]) and [[Josh West (Home and Away)|Josh West]] ([[Daniel Collopy]]). Noah and Hayley split the following year after Hayley kisses Josh and they begin seeing other people. [[Kit Hunter]] ([[Amy Mizzi]]) shows a romantic interest in Noah after he helps with her alcoholism but he rebuffs her.\n\nNoah and Hayley reunite after Hayley loses her memory in a car crash with [[Brodie Hanson]] ([[Susie Rugg]]). Hayley soon regains her memory and is devastated when she remembers [[Alex Poulos]] ([[Danny Raco]]), who she had been dating prior to the accident, has left her for Brodie. On the night of Hayley's 21st birthday, Noah proposes and she accepts. Hayley's suggestion of inviting Jill and having a church wedding does not sit well with Noah. In the end the couple marry in an outdoor ceremony along with [[Kane Phillips|Kane]] ([[Sam Atwell]]) and [[Kirsty Phillips]] ([[Christie Hayes]]), who are renewing their vows.\n\nWhen Sarah Lewis (Luisa Hastings-Edge) begins terrorizing Summer Bay wanting retribution for the death of her boyfriend, Felix Walters ([[Josh Lawson]]), she storms [[Leah Patterson-Baker|Leah Patterson]]'s ([[Ada Nicodemou]]) house where a number of Bay residents have gathered and she demands Felix's killer steps forward. Noah tries to explain that Sarah was the one who killed Felix by injecting him with [[Crystal Meth]]. After Sarah knocks Decetive Peter Baker ([[Nicholas Bishop]]) unconscious, she goes after Dani who arrives at the house, Noah follows Sarah and is shot dead in the process.\nSarah then turns the gun on herself and commits suicide. Following his death, Noah appears in many of Hayley's visions during the grieving process and makes one final appearance during the 2004 Season finale. In the Surf Club, a bar is built in Noah's memory named after him and a painting of him by Hayley remains on the wall for a number of years.\n\n==Reception==\nFor his portrayal of Noah, Brady was nominated for the \"Most Popular New Male Talent\" Logie in 2001.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=age&kw=tammin+sursok+and+home+and+away&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=ILL010403GIEKS1S8FQA|title=Lisa McCune still Logies darling|date=3 April 2001|work=[[Illawarra Mercury]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|page=5|accessdate=13 May 2013}}</ref> He was also nominated for the Silver Logie for \"Most Popular Actor\" for three years in a row from 2003 to 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?multiview=true&sy=nstore&page=1&kw=Beau+Brady&pb=all_ffx&dt=enterRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=article&rc=200&rm=200&sp=adv&clsPage=1&hids=&sids=SAG0305118J4DC34BHDE|title=Heeler loses Faith in Gold|first=Suzanne|last=Carbonne|work=[[Sunday Age]]|date=11 May 2003|accessdate=13 May 2013|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?multiview=true&sy=nstore&page=1&kw=Beau+Brady&pb=all_ffx&dt=enterRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=article&rc=200&rm=200&sp=adv&clsPage=1&hids=&sids=ILL0403237MBVV4MTMRU|date=23 March 2004|accessdate=13 May 2013|work= The Ilawarra Mercury|title=The Logie motions|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?multiview=true&sy=nstore&page=1&kw=Beau+Brady&pb=all_ffx&dt=enterRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=article&rc=200&rm=200&sp=adv&clsPage=1&hids=&sids=SHD050501VV5J01H53KG|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|date=1 May 2005|accessdate=13 May 2013|title=TV& Radio|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|first=Rachel|last=Browne}}</ref> The episode featuring Noah's funeral won writer Louise Crane-Bowes an [[Australian Writers Guild]] award in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awg.com.au/images/awgie%20winners%201968-2006.pdf|title=Winners 1968-2006|publisher=[[Australian Writers Guild]]|accessdate=24 July 2012|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029150956/http://www.awg.com.au/images/awgie%20winners%201968-2006.pdf|archive-date=29 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The episode featuring Noah's appearance as a ghost to say goodbye to Hayley also earned a nomination in this category in the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australiantelevision.net/awards/awgie2005.html|title=australian television information archive -AWGIE awards 2005}}</ref>\n\n[[Mark Juddery]] of ''[[The Sun-Herald]]'' described Noah's death at the hands of Sarah Lewis as the \"Biggest Event\" in the series' history in his article about television characters being killed off in order to boost ratings.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?multiview=true&sy=nstore&page=1&kw=Beau+Brady&pb=all_ffx&dt=enterRange&dr=1month&so=relevance&sf=article&rc=200&rm=200&sp=adv&clsPage=1&hids=&sids=SHD050306106JD4EB37L|title=\nDeath by popular vote|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|first=Mark|last=Judderry|date=6 March 2005|accessdate=13 May 2013|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Home and Away characters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lawson, Noah}}\n[[Category:Home and Away characters]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2000]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional murdered people in soap operas]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Decetive->Detective -Fix a typo in one click",