{"title_page": "Waternish", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n[[File:Isle of Skye UK relief location map labels.jpg|thumb|Map of Skye showing Waternish]]\n[[File:Western shore of Loch Bay - geograph.org.uk - 1233075.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Western shore of Loch Bay]]\n'''Waternish''' or '''Vaternish''' ({{lang-gd|Bh\u00e0tairnis}})<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duwe |first1=Kurt C. |title=Vol. 11: An t-Eilean Sgitheanach:  Trondairnis, Di\u00f9irinis & Minginis(Isle of Skye: Trotternish, Duirinish & Minginish) |url=http://www.linguae-celticae.org/dateien/Gaidhlig_Local_Studies_Vol_11_Trondairnis_Ed_II.pdf}}</ref> is a peninsula approximately {{convert|12|km|mi|abbr=on}} long on the island of [[Skye]], Scotland, situated between [[Loch Dunvegan]] and [[Loch Snizort]] in the northwest of the island, and traditionally inhabited and owned by [[Clan MacLeod]] whose clan seat is at the nearby [[Dunvegan Castle]]. The current clan chief is [[Hugh MacLeod of MacLeod]]. It contains the hamlets of [[Stein, Skye|Stein]] and [[Lusta]] in Loch Bay to the south east, [[Halistra]], [[Hallin]] and [[Trumpan]] further north and  [[Gillen, Skye|Gillen]] to the west, all of which are accessed from the A850 road by crossing the Fairy Bridge. The highest point is Ben Geary ({{convert|284|m|ft|abbr=on}}) and the most northerly is [[Waternish Point]]. The name Waternish is derived from the [[Old Norse]] {{lang|non|vatnenes}} or \"headland of the pond\", via Scottish Gaelic {{lang|gd|Bh\u00e0tairnis}}.\n\nThe history of the peninsula is a long (and often bloody) one involving clan feuds, massacres, de-population during the [[Highland Clearances]], and eventual re-vitalisation. Originally consisting of small crofting communities, Waternish now has a growing population and is home to various arts and crafts enterprises. Whilst the main industry on Waternish is tourism, there has also been a revival in recent years of [[crofting]] or [[small-scale agriculture]]. The local school is called Knockbreck. The school has struggled recently due to an ageing population which has resulted in only 4 students currently attending and the school was scheduled for closure in summer 2015.<ref>[https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/islands/inner-hebrides/457379/councillors-approve-plans-to-close-skye-schools/ Press and Journal 2015-01-15]</ref> The local pub is the Stein Inn, which dates back to 1790 and is the oldest on Skye.<ref>[http://www.steininn.co.uk/ \"Magical places do exist...\"] steininn.co.uk. Retrieved 6 June 2010.</ref>\n\nTrumpan was the site of the skirmish known as the [[Battle of the Spoiling Dyke]]<ref>[http://www.thehendrys.freeserve.co.uk/eigg/eigg.htm \"The Massacre at Trumpan Church and the subsequent Battle of the Spoiled Dyke\"]. The Hendry Family. Retrieved 25 May 2008.</ref> and the churchyard is the burial ground of [[Rachel Chiesley, Lady Grange]].<ref>Macauley (2009) p. 149</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Land raid]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* Macauley, Margaret (2009) ''The Prisoner of St Kilda: The true story of the unfortunate Lady Grange''. Edinburgh; Luath. {{ISBN|978-1-906817-02-2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category inline}}\n\n{{coord|57|32|20|N|6|34|30|W|region:GB_scale:100000|display=title}}\n{{Skye}}\n{{Scottish provinces|insular}}\n\n[[Category:Landforms of the Isle of Skye]]\n[[Category:Peninsulas of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Highland (council area)]]\n\n\n{{Highland-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n[[File:Isle of Skye UK relief location map labels.jpg|thumb|Map of Skye showing Waternish]]\n[[File:Western shore of Loch Bay - geograph.org.uk - 1233075.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Western shore of Loch Bay]]\n'''Waternish''' or '''Vaternish''' ({{lang-gd|Bh\u00e0tairnis}})<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duwe |first1=Kurt C. |title=Vol. 11: An t-Eilean Sgitheanach:  Trondairnis, Di\u00f9irinis & Minginis(Isle of Skye: Trotternish, Duirinish & Minginish) |url=http://www.linguae-celticae.org/dateien/Gaidhlig_Local_Studies_Vol_11_Trondairnis_Ed_II.pdf}}</ref> is a peninsula approximately {{convert|12|km|mi|abbr=on}} long on the island of [[Skye]], Scotland, situated between Loch Dunvegan and Loch Snizort in the northwest of the island, and traditionally inhabited and owned by [[Clan MacLeod]] whose clan seat is at the nearby [[Dunvegan Castle]]. The current clan chief is Hugh Macleod of Macleod. It contains the hamlets of [[Stein, Skye|Stein]] and [[Lusta]] in Loch Bay to the south east, [[Halistra]], [[Hallin]] and [[Trumpan]] further north and  [[Gillen, Skye|Gillen]] to the west, all of which are accessed from the A850 road by crossing the Fairy Bridge. The highest point is Ben Geary ({{convert|284|m|ft|abbr=on}}) and the most northerly is [[Waternish Point]]. The name Waternish is derived from the [[Old Norse]] {{lang|non|vatnenes}} or \"headland of the pond\", via Scottish Gaelic {{lang|gd|Bh\u00e0tairnis}}.\n\nThe history of the peninsula is a long (and often bloody) one involving clan feuds, massacres, de-population during the [[Highland Clearances]], and eventual re-vitalisation. Originally consisting of small crofting communities, Waternish now has a growing population and is home to various arts and crafts enterprises. Whilst the main industry on Waternish is tourism, there has also been a revival in recent years of [[crofting]] or [[small-scale agriculture]]. The local school is called Knockbreck. The school has struggled recently due to an ageing population which has resulted in only 4 students currently attending and the school was scheduled for closure in summer 2015.<ref>[https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/islands/inner-hebrides/457379/councillors-approve-plans-to-close-skye-schools/ Press and Journal 2015-01-15]</ref> The local pub is the Stein Inn, which dates back to 1790 and is the oldest on Skye.<ref>[http://www.steininn.co.uk/ \"Magical places do exist...\"] steininn.co.uk. Retrieved 6 June 2010.</ref>\n\nTrumpan was the site of the skirmish known as the [[Battle of the Spoiling Dyke]]<ref>[http://www.thehendrys.freeserve.co.uk/eigg/eigg.htm \"The Massacre at Trumpan Church and the subsequent Battle of the Spoiled Dyke\"]. The Hendry Family. Retrieved 25 May 2008.</ref> and the churchyard is the burial ground of [[Rachel Chiesley, Lady Grange]].<ref>Macauley (2009) p. 149</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Land raid]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* Macauley, Margaret (2009) ''The Prisoner of St Kilda: The true story of the unfortunate Lady Grange''. Edinburgh; Luath. {{ISBN|978-1-906817-02-2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{coord|57|32|20|N|6|34|30|W|region:GB_scale:100000|display=title}}\n{{Skye}}\n{{Scottish provinces|insular}}\n\n[[Category:Landforms of the Isle of Skye]]\n[[Category:Peninsulas of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Highland (council area)]]\n\n\n{{Highland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jellyman", "label": "safe", "comment": "added wikilinks; Commons link format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waternish"}
{"title_page": "The Creation of Adam", "text_new": "{{short description|Painting by Michelangelo}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| image=Michelangelo - Creation of Adam (cropped).jpg\n| title=The Creation of Adam\n| artist=Michelangelo\n| year=c. 1512\n| other_language_1=[[Italian language|Italian]]\n| other_title_1={{lang|it|Creazione di Adamo}}\n| type=[[Fresco]]\n| height_metric=280\n| width_metric=570\n| height_imperial=9\n| height_inch=2\n| width_imperial=18\n| width_inch=8\n| imperial_unit=ft\n| metric_unit=cm\n| dimensions_ref=<ref name=Gardner>{{cite book |first1=Helen |last1=Gardner |authorlink1=Helen Gardner (art historian) |first2=Fred S. |last2=Kleiner |title=Gardner's Art Through the Ages. A Concise Global History |url=https://books.google.com/?id=UX9TCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |year=2016 |origyear=[https://books.google.com/?id=6He93ZdZUHsC 2008] |edition=4th |publisher=[[Cengage Learning]] |location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]] |isbn=978-1-305-57780-0 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=UX9TCwAAQBAJ&pg=285 285]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Creation of Adam''''' ({{Lang-it|'''Creazione di Adamo'''}}) is a [[fresco]] painting by Italian artist [[Michelangelo]], which forms part of the [[Sistine Chapel ceiling|Sistine Chapel's ceiling]], painted c. 1508\u20131512. It illustrates the [[Bible|Biblical]] [[Genesis creation narrative|creation narrative]] from the [[Book of Genesis]] in which [[God the Father#Christianity|God]] gives life to [[Adam]], the first [[man]]. The fresco is part of a complex iconographic scheme and is chronologically the fourth in the series of panels depicting episodes from Genesis.\n\nThe image of the near-touching hands of God and Adam has become iconic of [[human|humanity.]] The painting has been reproduced in countless imitations and parodies.<ref name=Smithsonian>{{cite web | url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/The-Measure-of-Genius-Michelangelos-Sistine-Chapel-at-500.html | title=The Measure of Genius | first=Jamie |last=Katz | date=10 April 2009 | work=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian.com]] | accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> Michelangelo's ''Creation of Adam'' is one of the most replicated religious paintings of all time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://historylists.org/art/20-of-the-world%E2%80%99s-most-famous-art-pieces.html |title=20 of the World's Most Famous Art Pieces \u2013 History Lists |website=historylists.org |accessdate=23 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|Sistine Chapel ceiling}}\n[[File:Vatican-ChapelleSixtine-Plafond.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Michelangelo painted the ceiling of the [[Sistine Chapel]]; the work took approximately four years to complete (1508\u20131512)]]\nIn 1505 Michelangelo was invited back to Rome by the newly elected [[Pope Julius II]]. He was commissioned to build the [[Tomb of Pope Julius II|Pope's tomb]], which was to include forty statues and be finished in five years.\n\nUnder the patronage of the Pope, Michelangelo experienced constant interruptions to his work on the tomb in order to accomplish numerous other tasks. Although Michelangelo worked on the tomb for 40 years, it was never finished to his satisfaction.<ref name=\"Goldcheider14\">Goldscheider, pp. 14\u201316.</ref> It is located in the [[San Pietro in Vincoli|Church of S. Pietro in Vincoli]] in Rome and is most famous for his central figure of ''[[Moses (Michelangelo)|Moses]]'', completed in 1516.<ref name=Bartz134/> Of the other statues intended for the tomb, two known as the ''[[Rebellious Slave]]'' and the ''[[Dying Slave]]'', are now in the [[Louvre Museum|Louvre]].<ref name=Goldcheider14/>\n\nDuring the same period, Michelangelo painted the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel, which took approximately four years to complete (1508\u20131512).<ref name=Bartz134>Bartz and K\u00f6nig, p. 134.</ref> According to Condivi's account, [[Bramante]], who was working on the building of  [[St Peter's Basilica]], resented Michelangelo's commission for the Pope's tomb and convinced the Pope to commission him in a medium with which he was unfamiliar, in order that he might fail at the task.<ref>Coughlan, p. 112.</ref>\n\nMichelangelo was originally commissioned to paint the [[Twelve Apostles]] on the triangular pendentives that supported the ceiling, and cover the central part of the ceiling with ornament.<ref name= Goldscheider12>Goldscheider, pp. 12\u201314.</ref> Michelangelo persuaded Pope Julius to give him a free hand and proposed a different and more complex scheme, representing the [[Genesis creation story|Creation]], the [[Fall of Man]], the Promise of Salvation through the prophets, and the [[genealogy of Christ]]. The work is part of a larger scheme of decoration within the chapel which represents much of the doctrine of the Catholic Church.<ref name= Goldscheider12/>\n\nThe composition stretches over 500 square metres of ceiling,<ref>Bartz and K\u00f6nig, p. 43.</ref> and contains over 300 figures.<ref name= Goldscheider12/>  At its centre are nine episodes from the [[Book of Genesis]], divided into three groups: God's Creation of the Earth; God's Creation of Humankind and their fall from God's grace; and lastly, the state of Humanity as represented by [[Noah]] and his family. On the pendentives supporting the ceiling are painted twelve men and women who prophesied the coming of Jesus; seven [[prophet]]s of Israel and five [[Sibyl]]s, prophetic women of the Classical world.<ref name= Goldscheider12/>  Among the most famous paintings on the ceiling are ''The Creation of Adam'', ''[[Adam and Eve]] in the [[Garden of Eden]]'', the [[Deluge myth|''Deluge'']], the ''Prophet [[Jeremiah]]'' and the ''[[Cumaean Sibyl]]''.\n\n==Composition==\n[[Image:'Adam's Creation Sistine Chapel ceiling' by Michelangelo JBU33cut.jpg|right|600px]]\nGod is depicted as an elderly white-bearded caucasian man wrapped in a swirling cloak while Adam, on the lower left, is completely [[naked]]. God's right arm is outstretched to impart the spark of life from his own finger into that of Adam, whose left arm is extended in a pose mirroring God's, a reminder that man is created in the image and likeness of God ({{Bibleref2|Gen.|1:26|NRSV}}). Another point is that Adam's finger and God's finger aren't touching. It gives the impression that God, the giver of life, is reaching out to Adam who has yet to receive it; they [God and Adam] are not on \"the same level\" as would be two humans shaking hands, for instance.\n\nMany hypotheses have been formulated regarding the identity and meaning of the twelve figures around God. According to an interpretation that was first proposed by the English art critic [[Walter Pater]] (1839\u20131894) and is now widely accepted, the person protected by God's left arm represents [[Eve]], due to the figure's feminine appearance and gaze towards Adam,<ref name=\"Givens2009\">{{cite book |last=Givens |first=Terryl L. |authorlink=Terryl Givens |date=2009 |chapter=Prologue |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/?id=nZNODwAAQBAJ&pg=PT8&dq=Prologue |title=When Souls Had Wings. Pre-Mortal Existence in Western Thought |url=https://books.google.com/?id=nZNODwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |location=[[Oxford|Oxford, England]] |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-190-91448-6 |ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Steinberg1992\">{{cite journal |authorlink=Leo Steinberg |last1=Steinberg |first1=Leo |date=December 1992 |title=Who's who in Michelangelo's ''Creation of Adam'': A Chronology of the Picture's Reluctant Self-Revelation |journal=[[College Art Association|The Art Bulletin]] |volume=74 |issue=4 |pages=553\u2013554 |jstor=3045910 |doi=10.2307/3045910}}</ref> and the eleven other figures symbolically represent the souls of Adam and Eve's unborn progeny, the entire human race.<ref name=\"Givens2009\"/><ref name=\"Steinberg1992\"/> This interpretation has been challenged, mainly on the grounds that the Catholic Church regards the teaching of the [[pre-existence]] of souls as heretical.<ref name=\"Givens2009\"/><ref name=\"Steinberg1992\"/> Consequently, the figure behind God has also been suggested to be the [[Virgin Mary]], [[Sophia (wisdom)|Sophia]] (the personification of wisdom mentioned in the [[Book of Wisdom]]), the personified human soul, or \"an angel of masculine build\".<ref name=\"Givens2009\"/><ref name=\"Steinberg1992\"/>\n\n''The Creation of Adam'' is generally thought to depict the excerpt \"God created man in His own image, in the image of God He created him\" ({{Bibleref2|Gen.|1:27|NASB}}). The inspiration for Michelangelo's treatment of the subject may come from a [[medieval]] [[hymn]], \"[[Veni Creator Spiritus]]\", which asks the 'finger of the paternal right hand' (''digitus paternae dexterae'') to give the faithful speech.<ref>[http://www.preces-latinae.org/thesaurus/Hymni/VeniCreator.html Veni, Creator Spiritus / Come Holy Spirit, Creator Blest]. Preces-latinae.org.</ref>\n\n==Sources==\nMichelangelo's main source of inspiration for his Adam in his ''Creation of Adam'' may have been a [[Cameo (carving)|cameo]] showing a nude [[Augustus|Augustus Caesar]] riding sidesaddle on a [[Capricorn (astrology)|Capricorn]].<ref>[https://www.google.com/search?q=Augustus+cameo+Capricorn&tbm=isch&tbs=simg:CAQSlwEJGwdg-o1QHQkaiwELEKjU2AQaBAgACAMMCxCwjKcIGmIKYAgDEijbDq4EoQSdBPIEmAWfBZQMyg6KDPot2Cz2LdYs9S3XLPkt0yysNNokGjCdkvYlEVFK5y62noihfD2LNuTiYTQ8L9sSKoPkKJr2gtr0K7wWhossO7qKoQNfQPwgAwwLEI6u_1ggaCgoICAESBLELPQAM Cameo] on [[Google Images]].</ref> This cameo is now at [[Alnwick Castle]], [[Northumberland]].<ref>{{cite journal | last=Sutherland | first=Bruce | date=Winter 2013 | title=Cameo Appearances on the Sistine Ceiling | journal=Source: Notes in the History of Art | volume=32 | issue=2 | page=14 | publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]] | jstor=23292907| doi=10.1086/sou.32.2.23292907 }} Alnwick Castle is in Northumberland, not Northampton, as the captions state. The Duke of Northumberland who owns the cameos discussed in the article has expressed his appreciation in a letter to the author.</ref> The cameo used to belong to [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]] [[Domenico Grimani]] who lived in Rome while Michelangelo painted the ceiling. Evidence suggests that Michelangelo and Grimani were friends. This cameo offers an alternative theory for those scholars who have been dissatisfied with the theory that Michelangelo was mainly inspired by [[Lorenzo Ghiberti]]'s Adam in his ''Creation of Adam''.<ref>Sutherland, Bruce (Winter 2013). pp. 12\u201318.</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n|title= Detail\n|align=center|total_width=450\n|image1=Michelangelo, Creation of Adam 05.jpg|caption1=Adam\n|alt1=Clean-shaven man with short brown hair\n|image2=Hands of God and Adam.jpg|caption2=The hands\n|alt2=Hand of God reaching out to Adam who receives it\n|image3=Michelangelo, Creation of Adam 06.jpg|caption3=God\n|alt3=Bearded man with long white hair\n}}\n\n==Analysis==\nSeveral hypotheses have been put forward about the meaning of ''The Creation of Adam'''s highly original composition, many of them taking Michelangelo's well-documented expertise in human anatomy as their starting point.\n\n===Portrayal of the human brain===\nIn 1990 in [[Anderson, Indiana]], [[physician]] Frank  Meshberger noted in the ''[[Journal of the American Medical Association]]'' that the background figures and shapes portrayed behind the figure of God appeared to be an anatomically accurate picture of the [[human brain]].<ref name=Meshberger>{{cite journal | last1=Meshberger| first1=Frank Lynn|date=10 October 1990 |title=An Interpretation of Michelangelo's Creation of Adam Based on Neuroanatomy |journal=[[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]] |volume=264 |issue=14 |pages=1837\u201341 |doi=10.1001/jama.1990.03450140059034|pmid=2205727 |pmc= }} [https://scholar.google.com/scholar?cluster=1229086804171881877 Pdf]. [http://www.mentalhealthandillness.com/creation_fr.html Excerpt] on Mental Health & Illness.com. Retrieved 21 September 2010.</ref> On close examination, borders in the painting correlate with major [[Sulcus (neuroanatomy)|sulci]] of the [[telencephalon|cerebrum]] in the inner and outer surface of the brain, the [[brain stem]], the [[frontal lobe]], the basilar artery, the [[pituitary gland]] and the [[optic chiasm]].<ref name=Meshberger/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/michelangelos-secret-message-in-the-sistine-chapel-a-juxtaposition-of-god-and-the-human-brain/ | title=Michelangelo's secret message in the Sistine Chapel: A juxtaposition of God and the human brain | first=R. Douglas |last=Fields | date=27 May 2010 | work=[[Scientific American]] | accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref>\nWhy\n\n===Portrayal of the birth process===\nAlternatively, it has been observed that the red cloth around God has the shape of a\nhuman [[uterus]] (one art historian has called it a \"uterine mantle\"<ref>{{cite book |editor-first=Adrian |editor-last=Stokes |editor-link=Adrian Stokes (critic) |title=Michelangelo. A study in the nature of art |url=https://books.google.com/?id=4QxTAQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |year=2013 |origyear=[https://books.google.com/?id=MqRPAAAAMAAJ 1955] |publisher=[[Routledge]] |location=[[Abingdon-on-Thames]] |isbn=978-1-136-44293-3 |page=[https://books.google.com/?&id=4QxTAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA89&dq=%22uterine+mantle%22%22Creation+of+Adam%22 89]}}</ref>) and that the scarf hanging out, coloured green, could be a newly cut [[umbilical cord]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bruschini |first=Enrico |title=Masterpieces of the Vatican |url=https://books.google.com/?id=O7QzAQAAIAAJ |year=2004 |publisher=Edizioni Musei Vaticani |location=[[Vatican City]] |isbn=978-8-881-17088-3 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=O7QzAQAAIAAJ&q=%22recently+an+American+gynaecologist,+observing+the+profile+of+the+red+mantle,+noted+an+outstanding+resemblance+to+the+human+uterus.+The+green+cord+trailing+below+the+mantle+corresponds+exactly+with+an+umbilical+cord+that+has+just+been+cut.%22 112]}}</ref> Recently a group of Italian researchers published on ''[[Mayo Clinic Proceedings]]'' an article where the images of the mantle and the postpartum uterus were overlapped.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Di Bella |first1=Stefano |title=The \"Delivery\" of Adam: A Medical Interpretation of Michelangelo |url=http://www.mayoclinicproceedings.org/article/S0025-6196%2815%2900153-6/fulltext?mobileUi=0 |journal=[[Mayo Clinic Proceedings]] |date=2015 |volume=90 |issue=4 |pages=505\u2013508 |doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2015.02.007 |pmid=25841253|doi-access=free }}</ref> According to Enrico Bruschini (2004), \"This is an interesting hypothesis that presents the Creation scene as an idealised representation of the physical birth of man (\"The Creation\"). It explains the [[navel]] that appears on [[Adam]], which is at first perplexing because he was created, not born of a woman.\"<ref>Bruschini, Enrico (2004). p. [https://books.google.com/?id=O7QzAQAAIAAJ&q=%22This+is+an+interesting+hypothesis+that+presents+the+Creation+scene+as+an+idealised+representation+of+the+physical+birth+of+man.+It+explains+the+navel+that+appears+on+Adam,+which+is+at+first+perplexing+because+he+was+created,+not+born+of+a+woman.%22 112].</ref>\n\n=== Portrayal of Eve's Rib ===\nAdditionally, Deivis Campos notes in ''[[Clinical Anatomy|Clinical Anatomy Journal]]'' that the left side of [[Adam]]\u2019s [[torso]] contains an extra concealed [[rib]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Campos|first=Deivis de|date=2019|title=A hidden rib found in Michelangelo Buonarroti's fresco The Creation of Adam|journal=Clinical Anatomy|language=en|volume=32|issue=5|pages=648\u2013653|doi=10.1002/ca.23363|pmid=30820963|issn=1098-2353}}</ref> Due to Michelangelo\u2019s in-depth knowledge of human anatomy, he insinuates that this rib outline is intentional, and represents the rib of [[Eve]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nCampos suggests that this extra rib inclusion was a way for Michelangelo to represent Adam and Eve being created side by side, which differs from the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] tradition that states Eve was created after Adam.<ref name=\":0\" /> There is significant evidence that Michelangelo radically disagreed with many Catholic traditions and had a tumultuous relationship with the commissioner of the ceiling, [[Art patronage of Julius II|Pope Julius II]]. Thus, Campos suggests that the rib inclusion was an intentional way to slight Pope Julius II and the Catholic Church, without having to admit fault, as very few people knew anything about human anatomy at the time and could challenge the piece.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, in the book of Genesis the creation of men and women has two versions: Gen 2, 22<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biblehub.com/genesis/2-22.htm|title=Genesis 2:22 And from the rib that the LORD God had taken from the man, He made a woman and brought her to him.|website=biblehub.com|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> is the creation of Eve from the rib of Adam, but before this, in Gen 1, 27,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biblehub.com/genesis/1-27.htm|title=Genesis 1:27 So God created man in His own image; in the image of God He created him; male and female He created them.|website=biblehub.com|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> there is another story when male and female were created side by side: \"So God created mankind in his own image, in the image of God he created them; male and female he created them\". So, at least for this rib, there is no support for the assumption that Michelangelo was against any Catholic tradition.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n== Critical Sketches ==\n[[Michelangelo]] was a prolific [[Drafter|draftsman]], as he was trained in a Florentine workshop at a dynamic time in the art scene, when paper had become readily available in sufficient quantity.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Wright|first=Alison|date=2007-06-01|title=Michelangelo Drawings: Closer to the Master|journal=Renaissance Studies|language=en|volume=21|issue=3|pages=415\u2013422|doi=10.1111/j.1477-4658.2007.00414.x|issn=1477-4658}}</ref> As follows, sketching was the first step in Michelangelo\u2019s artistic process, as it helped him plan his final paintings and sculptural pieces.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wright|first=Alison|date=2007-06-01|title=Michelangelo Drawings: Closer to the Master|journal=Renaissance Studies|language=en|volume=21|issue=3|pages=416\u2013418|doi=10.1111/j.1477-4658.2007.00414.x|issn=1477-4658}}</ref> Thus, [[Michelangelo|Michelangelo\u2019s]] sketches provide a critical link between his creative vision and final compositions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jstor.org/journal/britmusequar|title=The British Museum Quarterly on JSTOR|website=www.jstor.org|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> His genius is especially evident through his sheets \u201cfilled with multiple figures and close studies of human anatomy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clevelandart.org/exhibitions/michelangelo-mind-master|title=Michelangelo: Mind of the Master|last=kmagerkurth|date=2019-03-11|website=Cleveland Museum of Art|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Creation of Adam Studies ===\nMichelangelo completed two sketches in [[Rome]] in preparation for the Creation of Adam scene. They are both on display in the [[British Museum]] in [[London]], revealing Michelangelo\u2019s in depth planning process for the [[Sistine Chapel ceiling]] composition, and his serious attention to perspective and shadowing <ref name=\":1\" />. \n\nThe first, is a ''[https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details/collection_image_gallery.aspx?assetId=6632001&objectId=671387&partId=1 Scheme for the Decoration of the Vault of the Sistine Chapel: Studies of Arms and Hands]''.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=671387&page=1&partId=1&peoA=114829-2-9&people=114829|title=drawing|website=British Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> The right side of the page was sketched in 1508 with black chalk, and is a study of [[Adam|Adam\u2019s]] limp hand, before it is ignited with the gift of life from [[God]], in the Creation of Adam scene. Michelangelo sketched this over a previous brown, lead point [[stylus]] study of the vaulted [[Sistine Chapel ceiling]]<ref name=\":2\" />. The entire composition is 274 millimeters in height and 386 millimeters in width<ref name=\":2\" />. The second sketch is titled ''[https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details/collection_image_gallery.aspx?assetId=200159001&objectId=716122&partId=1 Studies of a Reclining Male Nude: Adam in the Fresco \u2018The Creation of Man.\u2019]'' It was created in 1511 in dark red chalk, over a stylus under drawing.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?images=true&museumno=1926,1009.1&objectId=716122&page=1&partId=1|title=drawing|website=British Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Red chalk was Michelangelo\u2019s preferred medium at this period of time, as it could be shaved to a finer point than black chalk. Michelangelo used this fine point to create a scintillating skin surface, that was unique for this particular sketch, and is not seen in his later works<ref name=\":1\" />. The recto drawing is 193 millimeters in height and 259 millimeters in width<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\n=== Studies of a Reclining Male Nude: Adam in the Fresco 'The Creation of Man' ===\nIn the ''[https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details/collection_image_gallery.aspx?assetId=200159001&objectId=716122&partId=1 Studies of a Reclining Male Nude: Adam in the Fresco \u2018The Creation of Man]'', Adam is resting on earth, propped up by his forearm, with his thighs spread out and his torso slightly twisted to the side<ref name=\":3\" />. Michelangelo employed a male model to capture this effortful pose and used his red chalk to develop thick contours, in order to establish a definitive form, so every [[Sistine Chapel|chapel]] visitor could clearly recognize the muscular body from standing on the floor, 68 feet below the [[Sistine Chapel ceiling|ceiling]]<ref name=\":3\" />. \n\nIn Michelangelo\u2019s final fresco on the [[Sistine Chapel ceiling|ceiling]], Adam is physically beautiful, but spiritually still incomplete.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barolsky|first=Paul|date=2001|journal=Source: Notes in the History of Art|volume=20|issue=4|pages=6\u20138|issn=0737-4453|jstor=23206730|title=The Imperfection of Michelangelo's Adam|doi=10.1086/sou.20.4.23206730}}</ref> The sketch prefaces this story, as it is also incomplete in the sense that the only complete component of the drawing is Adam\u2019s twisted torso. Adam\u2019s other limbs bleed off of the trimmed page in immature form<ref name=\":1\" />. However, the work is not \u201cunfinished,\u201d as it reached its purpose for Michelangelo, which was to work out the details of the torso in the medium of chalk, so he was confident in the composition when he began the actual, permanent [[fresco]] panel.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.michelangelo.net/|title=Michelangelo Paintings, Sculptures & Artwork|website=www.michelangelo.net|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n==== Context ====\nMichelangelo heavily studied the human body and dissected numerous [[Cadaver|cadavers]] in his artistic career, and overtime became captivated by the male torso<ref name=\":4\" />. In his [[De pictura|treatises on painting and sculpture]], [[Leon Battista Alberti]], defined the male figure as a \"geometrical and harmonious sum of its parts<ref name=\":1\" />.\" Michelangelo however, felt that the torso was the powerhouse of the male body, and therefore warranted significant attention and mass in his art pieces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hekint.org/2018/04/11/anatomy-michelangelo-1475-1564/|title=The Anatomy of Michelangelo (1475-1564) - Hektoen International|website=hekint.org|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Thus, the torso in the ''Study'' represents an idealization of the male form, \u201csymbolic of the perfection of God\u2019s creation before [[Fall of man|the fall]]<ref name=\":3\" />.\"\n\n==== Sources ====\nMichelangelo\u2019s inspiration for the torso in the [https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details/collection_image_gallery.aspx?assetId=200159001&objectId=716122&partId=1 ''Studies of a Reclining Male Nude: Adam in the Fresco \u2018The Creation of Man''] sketch, is believed to be the [[Belvedere Torso]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/exhibitions/the-vaticans-belvedere-torso-british-museum-216945|title=The Vatican's Belvedere Torso Heads to London|date=2015-01-08|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> The [[Belvedere Torso]] is a fragmentary [[Marble sculpture|marble statue]] that is a 1<sup>st</sup> century BC Roman copy of an ancient Greek sculpture. Michelangelo historically used ancient, classical statuary as inspiration for the human physique in his great masterpieces<ref name=\":5\" />. In 2015, the [[Belvedere Torso]] was displayed with Michelangelo\u2019s sketch in the \u201cDefining Beauty: The Body in Ancient Greek Art\u201d show at the [[British Museum|British Museum in London]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/defining-beauty-the-body-in-ancient-greek-art-at-the-british-museum-gives-visitors-quite-an-eyeful-10123257.html|title=The British Museum's new exhibition on the body in Ancient Greek art gives visitors an eyeful|date=2015-03-21|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Fair as the young men of the [[Elgin marbles]], the Adam of the Sistine Chapel is unlike them in a total absence of that balance and completeness which express so well the sentiment of a self-contained, independent life. In that languid figure there is something rude and [[satyr]]-like, something akin to the rugged hillside on which it lies. His whole form is gathered into an expression of mere expectation and reception; he has hardly strength enough to lift his finger to touch the finger of the creator; yet a touch of the finger-tips will suffice.|author=[[Walter Pater]]|title=''The Renaissance: Studies in Art and Poetry''|source=\"The Poetry of Michelangelo\"}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n*{{slink|Apophatic theology#Western Christianity}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category inline|Sistine Chapel ceiling - Creation of Adam|Sistine Chapel ceiling - ''Creation of Adam''}}\n* [http://www.michelangelomodels.com Models of wax and clay used by Michelangelo in making his sculpture and paintings]\n\n{{Sistine Chapel}}\n{{Michelangelo}}\n{{Adam and Eve}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Creation Of Adam}}\n[[Category:1512 paintings]]\n[[Category:Paintings depicting Adam and Eve]]\n[[Category:Paintings of gods]]\n[[Category:Sistine Chapel ceiling]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Painting by Michelangelo}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| image=Michelangelo - Creation of Adam (cropped).jpg\n| title=The Creation of Adam\n| artist=Michelangelo\n| year=c. 1512\n| other_language_1=[[Italian language|Italian]]\n| other_title_1={{lang|it|Creazione di Adamo}}\n| type=[[Fresco]]\n| height_metric=280\n| width_metric=570\n| height_imperial=9\n| height_inch=2\n| width_imperial=18\n| width_inch=8\n| imperial_unit=ft\n| metric_unit=cm\n| dimensions_ref=<ref name=Gardner>{{cite book |first1=Helen |last1=Gardner |authorlink1=Helen Gardner (art historian) |first2=Fred S. |last2=Kleiner |title=Gardner's Art Through the Ages. A Concise Global History |url=https://books.google.com/?id=UX9TCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |year=2016 |origyear=[https://books.google.com/?id=6He93ZdZUHsC 2008] |edition=4th |publisher=[[Cengage Learning]] |location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]] |isbn=978-1-305-57780-0 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=UX9TCwAAQBAJ&pg=285 285]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Creation of Adam''''' ({{Lang-it|'''Creazione di Adamo'''}}) is a [[fresco]] painting by Italian artist [[Michelangelo]], which forms part of the [[Sistine Chapel ceiling|Sistine Chapel's ceiling]], painted c. 1508\u20131512. It illustrates the [[Bible|Biblical]] [[Genesis creation narrative|creation narrative]] from the [[Book of Genesis]] in which [[God the Father#Christianity|God]] gives life to [[Adam]], the first [[man]]. The fresco is part of a complex iconographic scheme and is chronologically the fourth in the series of panels depicting episodes from Genesis.\n\nThe image of the near-touching hands of God and Adam has become iconic of [[human|humanity.]] The painting has been reproduced in countless imitations and parodies.<ref name=Smithsonian>{{cite web | url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/The-Measure-of-Genius-Michelangelos-Sistine-Chapel-at-500.html | title=The Measure of Genius | first=Jamie |last=Katz | date=10 April 2009 | work=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian.com]] | accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> Michelangelo's ''Creation of Adam'' is one of the most replicated religious paintings of all time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://historylists.org/art/20-of-the-world%E2%80%99s-most-famous-art-pieces.html |title=20 of the World's Most Famous Art Pieces \u2013 History Lists |website=historylists.org |accessdate=23 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|Sistine Chapel ceiling}}\n[[File:Vatican-ChapelleSixtine-Plafond.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Michelangelo painted the ceiling of the [[Sistine Chapel]]; the work took approximately four years to complete (1508\u20131512)]]\nIn 1505 Michelangelo was invited back to Rome by the newly elected [[Pope Julius II]]. He was commissioned to build the [[Tomb of Pope Julius II|Pope's tomb]], which was to include forty statues and be finished in five years.\n\nUnder the patronage of the Pope, Michelangelo experienced constant interruptions to his work on the tomb in order to accomplish numerous other tasks. Although Michelangelo worked on the tomb for 40 years, it was never finished to his satisfaction.<ref name=\"Goldcheider14\">Goldscheider, pp. 14\u201316.</ref> It is located in the [[San Pietro in Vincoli|Church of S. Pietro in Vincoli]] in Rome and is most famous for his central figure of ''[[Moses (Michelangelo)|Moses]]'', completed in 1516.<ref name=Bartz134/> Of the other statues intended for the tomb, two known as the ''[[Rebellious Slave]]'' and the ''[[Dying Slave]]'', are now in the [[Louvre Museum|Louvre]].<ref name=Goldcheider14/>\n\nDuring the same period, Michelangelo painted the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel, which took approximately four years to complete (1508\u20131512).<ref name=Bartz134>Bartz and K\u00f6nig, p. 134.</ref> According to Condivi's account, [[Bramante]], who was working on the building of  [[St Peter's Basilica]], resented Michelangelo's commission for the Pope's tomb and convinced the Pope to commission him in a medium with which he was unfamiliar, in order that he might fail at the task.<ref>Coughlan, p. 112.</ref>\n\nMichelangelo was originally commissioned to paint the [[Twelve Apostles]] on the triangular pendentives that supported the ceiling, and cover the central part of the ceiling with ornament.<ref name= Goldscheider12>Goldscheider, pp. 12\u201314.</ref> Michelangelo persuaded Pope Julius to give him a free hand and proposed a different and more complex scheme, representing the [[Genesis creation story|Creation]], the [[Fall of Man]], the Promise of Salvation through the prophets, and the [[genealogy of Christ]]. The work is part of a larger scheme of decoration within the chapel which represents much of the doctrine of the Catholic Church.<ref name= Goldscheider12/>\n\nThe composition stretches over 500 square metres of ceiling,<ref>Bartz and K\u00f6nig, p. 43.</ref> and contains over 300 figures.<ref name= Goldscheider12/>  At its centre are nine episodes from the [[Book of Genesis]], divided into three groups: God's Creation of the Earth; God's Creation of Humankind and their fall from God's grace; and lastly, the state of Humanity as represented by [[Noah]] and his family. On the pendentives supporting the ceiling are painted twelve men and women who prophesied the coming of Jesus; seven [[prophet]]s of Israel and five [[Sibyl]]s, prophetic women of the Classical world.<ref name= Goldscheider12/>  Among the most famous paintings on the ceiling are ''The Creation of Adam'', ''[[Adam and Eve]] in the [[Garden of Eden]]'', the [[Deluge myth|''Deluge'']], the ''Prophet [[Jeremiah]]'' and the ''[[Cumaean Sibyl]]''.\n\n==Composition==\n[[Image:'Adam's Creation Sistine Chapel ceiling' by Michelangelo JBU33cut.jpg|right|600px]]\nGod is depicted as an elderly white-bearded caucasian man wrapped in a swirling cloak while Adam, on the lower left, is completely [[naked]]. God's right arm is outstretched to impart the spark of life from his own finger into that of Adam, whose left arm is extended in a pose mirroring God's, a reminder that man is created in the image and likeness of God ({{Bibleref2|Gen.|1:26|NRSV}}). Another point is that Adam's finger and God's finger aren't touching. It gives the impression that God, the giver of life, is reaching out to Adam who has yet to receive it; they [God and Adam] are not on \"the same level\" as would be two humans shaking hands, for instance.\n\nMany hypotheses have been formulated regarding the identity and meaning of the twelve figures around God. According to an interpretation that was first proposed by the English art critic [[Walter Pater]] (1839\u20131894) and is now widely accepted, the person protected by God's left arm represents [[Eve]], due to the figure's feminine appearance and gaze towards Adam,<ref name=\"Givens2009\">{{cite book |last=Givens |first=Terryl L. |authorlink=Terryl Givens |date=2009 |chapter=Prologue |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/?id=nZNODwAAQBAJ&pg=PT8&dq=Prologue |title=When Souls Had Wings. Pre-Mortal Existence in Western Thought |url=https://books.google.com/?id=nZNODwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |location=[[Oxford|Oxford, England]] |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-190-91448-6 |ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Steinberg1992\">{{cite journal |authorlink=Leo Steinberg |last1=Steinberg |first1=Leo |date=December 1992 |title=Who's who in Michelangelo's ''Creation of Adam'': A Chronology of the Picture's Reluctant Self-Revelation |journal=[[College Art Association|The Art Bulletin]] |volume=74 |issue=4 |pages=553\u2013554 |jstor=3045910 |doi=10.2307/3045910}}</ref> and the eleven other figures symbolically represent the souls of Adam and Eve's unborn progeny, the entire human race.<ref name=\"Givens2009\"/><ref name=\"Steinberg1992\"/> This interpretation has been challenged, mainly on the grounds that the Catholic Church regards the teaching of the [[pre-existence]] of souls as heretical.<ref name=\"Givens2009\"/><ref name=\"Steinberg1992\"/> Consequently, the figure behind God has also been suggested to be the [[Virgin Mary]], [[Sophia (wisdom)|Sophia]] (the personification of wisdom mentioned in the [[Book of Wisdom]]), the personified human soul, or \"an angel of masculine build\".<ref name=\"Givens2009\"/><ref name=\"Steinberg1992\"/>\n\n''The Creation of Adam'' is generally thought to depict the excerpt \"God created man in His own image, in the image of God He created him\" ({{Bibleref2|Gen.|1:27|NASB}}). The inspiration for Michelangelo's treatment of the subject may come from a [[medieval]] [[hymn]], \"[[Veni Creator Spiritus]]\", which asks the 'finger of the paternal right hand' (''digitus paternae dexterae'') to give the faithful speech.<ref>[http://www.preces-latinae.org/thesaurus/Hymni/VeniCreator.html Veni, Creator Spiritus / Come Holy Spirit, Creator Blest]. Preces-latinae.org.</ref>\n\n==Sources==\nMichelangelo's main source of inspiration for his Adam in his ''Creation of Adam'' may have been a [[Cameo (carving)|cameo]] showing a nude [[Augustus|Augustus Caesar]] riding sidesaddle on a [[Capricorn (astrology)|Capricorn]].<ref>[https://www.google.com/search?q=Augustus+cameo+Capricorn&tbm=isch&tbs=simg:CAQSlwEJGwdg-o1QHQkaiwELEKjU2AQaBAgACAMMCxCwjKcIGmIKYAgDEijbDq4EoQSdBPIEmAWfBZQMyg6KDPot2Cz2LdYs9S3XLPkt0yysNNokGjCdkvYlEVFK5y62noihfD2LNuTiYTQ8L9sSKoPkKJr2gtr0K7wWhossO7qKoQNfQPwgAwwLEI6u_1ggaCgoICAESBLELPQAM Cameo] on [[Google Images]].</ref> This cameo is now at [[Alnwick Castle]], [[Northumberland]].<ref>{{cite journal | last=Sutherland | first=Bruce | date=Winter 2013 | title=Cameo Appearances on the Sistine Ceiling | journal=Source: Notes in the History of Art | volume=32 | issue=2 | page=14 | publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]] | jstor=23292907| doi=10.1086/sou.32.2.23292907 }} Alnwick Castle is in Northumberland, not Northampton, as the captions state. The Duke of Northumberland who owns the cameos discussed in the article has expressed his appreciation in a letter to the author.</ref> The cameo used to belong to [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]] [[Domenico Grimani]] who lived in Rome while Michelangelo painted the ceiling. Evidence suggests that Michelangelo and Grimani were friends. This cameo offers an alternative theory for those scholars who have been dissatisfied with the theory that Michelangelo was mainly inspired by [[Lorenzo Ghiberti]]'s Adam in his ''Creation of Adam''.<ref>Sutherland, Bruce (Winter 2013). pp. 12\u201318.</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n|title= Detail\n|align=center|total_width=450\n|image1=Michelangelo, Creation of Adam 05.jpg|caption1=Adam\n|alt1=Clean-shaven man with short brown hair\n|image2=Hands of God and Adam.jpg|caption2=The hands\n|alt2=Hand of God reaching out to Adam who receives it\n|image3=Michelangelo, Creation of Adam 06.jpg|caption3=God\n|alt3=Bearded man with long white hair\n}}\n\n==Analysis==\nSeveral hypotheses have been put forward about the meaning of ''The Creation of Adam'''s highly original composition, many of them taking Michelangelo's well-documented expertise in human anatomy as their starting point.\n\n===Portrayal of the human brain===\nIn 1990 in [[Anderson, Indiana]], [[physician]] Frank  Meshberger noted in the ''[[Journal of the American Medical Association]]'' that the background figures and shapes portrayed behind the figure of God appeared to be an anatomically accurate picture of the [[human brain]].<ref name=Meshberger>{{cite journal | last1=Meshberger| first1=Frank Lynn|date=10 October 1990 |title=An Interpretation of Michelangelo's Creation of Adam Based on Neuroanatomy |journal=[[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]] |volume=264 |issue=14 |pages=1837\u201341 |doi=10.1001/jama.1990.03450140059034|pmid=2205727 |pmc= }} [https://scholar.google.com/scholar?cluster=1229086804171881877 Pdf]. [http://www.mentalhealthandillness.com/creation_fr.html Excerpt] on Mental Health & Illness.com. Retrieved 21 September 2010.</ref> On close examination, borders in the painting correlate with major [[Sulcus (neuroanatomy)|sulci]] of the [[telencephalon|cerebrum]] in the inner and outer surface of the brain, the [[brain stem]], the [[frontal lobe]], the basilar artery, the [[pituitary gland]] and the [[optic chiasm]].<ref name=Meshberger/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/michelangelos-secret-message-in-the-sistine-chapel-a-juxtaposition-of-god-and-the-human-brain/ | title=Michelangelo's secret message in the Sistine Chapel: A juxtaposition of God and the human brain | first=R. Douglas |last=Fields | date=27 May 2010 | work=[[Scientific American]] | accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Portrayal of the birth process===\nAlternatively, it has been observed that the red cloth around God has the shape of a\nhuman [[uterus]] (one art historian has called it a \"uterine mantle\"<ref>{{cite book |editor-first=Adrian |editor-last=Stokes |editor-link=Adrian Stokes (critic) |title=Michelangelo. A study in the nature of art |url=https://books.google.com/?id=4QxTAQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |year=2013 |origyear=[https://books.google.com/?id=MqRPAAAAMAAJ 1955] |publisher=[[Routledge]] |location=[[Abingdon-on-Thames]] |isbn=978-1-136-44293-3 |page=[https://books.google.com/?&id=4QxTAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA89&dq=%22uterine+mantle%22%22Creation+of+Adam%22 89]}}</ref>) and that the scarf hanging out, coloured green, could be a newly cut [[umbilical cord]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bruschini |first=Enrico |title=Masterpieces of the Vatican |url=https://books.google.com/?id=O7QzAQAAIAAJ |year=2004 |publisher=Edizioni Musei Vaticani |location=[[Vatican City]] |isbn=978-8-881-17088-3 |page=[https://books.google.com/?id=O7QzAQAAIAAJ&q=%22recently+an+American+gynaecologist,+observing+the+profile+of+the+red+mantle,+noted+an+outstanding+resemblance+to+the+human+uterus.+The+green+cord+trailing+below+the+mantle+corresponds+exactly+with+an+umbilical+cord+that+has+just+been+cut.%22 112]}}</ref> Recently a group of Italian researchers published on ''[[Mayo Clinic Proceedings]]'' an article where the images of the mantle and the postpartum uterus were overlapped.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Di Bella |first1=Stefano |title=The \"Delivery\" of Adam: A Medical Interpretation of Michelangelo |url=http://www.mayoclinicproceedings.org/article/S0025-6196%2815%2900153-6/fulltext?mobileUi=0 |journal=[[Mayo Clinic Proceedings]] |date=2015 |volume=90 |issue=4 |pages=505\u2013508 |doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2015.02.007 |pmid=25841253|doi-access=free }}</ref> According to Enrico Bruschini (2004), \"This is an interesting hypothesis that presents the Creation scene as an idealised representation of the physical birth of man (\"The Creation\"). It explains the [[navel]] that appears on [[Adam]], which is at first perplexing because he was created, not born of a woman.\"<ref>Bruschini, Enrico (2004). p. [https://books.google.com/?id=O7QzAQAAIAAJ&q=%22This+is+an+interesting+hypothesis+that+presents+the+Creation+scene+as+an+idealised+representation+of+the+physical+birth+of+man.+It+explains+the+navel+that+appears+on+Adam,+which+is+at+first+perplexing+because+he+was+created,+not+born+of+a+woman.%22 112].</ref>\n\n=== Portrayal of Eve's Rib ===\nAdditionally, Deivis Campos notes in ''[[Clinical Anatomy|Clinical Anatomy Journal]]'' that the left side of [[Adam]]\u2019s [[torso]] contains an extra concealed [[rib]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Campos|first=Deivis de|date=2019|title=A hidden rib found in Michelangelo Buonarroti's fresco The Creation of Adam|journal=Clinical Anatomy|language=en|volume=32|issue=5|pages=648\u2013653|doi=10.1002/ca.23363|pmid=30820963|issn=1098-2353}}</ref> Due to Michelangelo\u2019s in-depth knowledge of human anatomy, he insinuates that this rib outline is intentional, and represents the rib of [[Eve]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nCampos suggests that this extra rib inclusion was a way for Michelangelo to represent Adam and Eve being created side by side, which differs from the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] tradition that states Eve was created after Adam.<ref name=\":0\" /> There is significant evidence that Michelangelo radically disagreed with many Catholic traditions and had a tumultuous relationship with the commissioner of the ceiling, [[Art patronage of Julius II|Pope Julius II]]. Thus, Campos suggests that the rib inclusion was an intentional way to slight Pope Julius II and the Catholic Church, without having to admit fault, as very few people knew anything about human anatomy at the time and could challenge the piece.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, in the book of Genesis the creation of men and women has two versions: Gen 2, 22<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biblehub.com/genesis/2-22.htm|title=Genesis 2:22 And from the rib that the LORD God had taken from the man, He made a woman and brought her to him.|website=biblehub.com|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> is the creation of Eve from the rib of Adam, but before this, in Gen 1, 27,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biblehub.com/genesis/1-27.htm|title=Genesis 1:27 So God created man in His own image; in the image of God He created him; male and female He created them.|website=biblehub.com|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> there is another story when male and female were created side by side: \"So God created mankind in his own image, in the image of God he created them; male and female he created them\". So, at least for this rib, there is no support for the assumption that Michelangelo was against any Catholic tradition.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n== Critical Sketches ==\n[[Michelangelo]] was a prolific [[Drafter|draftsman]], as he was trained in a Florentine workshop at a dynamic time in the art scene, when paper had become readily available in sufficient quantity.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Wright|first=Alison|date=2007-06-01|title=Michelangelo Drawings: Closer to the Master|journal=Renaissance Studies|language=en|volume=21|issue=3|pages=415\u2013422|doi=10.1111/j.1477-4658.2007.00414.x|issn=1477-4658}}</ref> As follows, sketching was the first step in Michelangelo\u2019s artistic process, as it helped him plan his final paintings and sculptural pieces.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wright|first=Alison|date=2007-06-01|title=Michelangelo Drawings: Closer to the Master|journal=Renaissance Studies|language=en|volume=21|issue=3|pages=416\u2013418|doi=10.1111/j.1477-4658.2007.00414.x|issn=1477-4658}}</ref> Thus, [[Michelangelo|Michelangelo\u2019s]] sketches provide a critical link between his creative vision and final compositions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jstor.org/journal/britmusequar|title=The British Museum Quarterly on JSTOR|website=www.jstor.org|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> His genius is especially evident through his sheets \u201cfilled with multiple figures and close studies of human anatomy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clevelandart.org/exhibitions/michelangelo-mind-master|title=Michelangelo: Mind of the Master|last=kmagerkurth|date=2019-03-11|website=Cleveland Museum of Art|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Creation of Adam Studies ===\nMichelangelo completed two sketches in [[Rome]] in preparation for the Creation of Adam scene. They are both on display in the [[British Museum]] in [[London]], revealing Michelangelo\u2019s in depth planning process for the [[Sistine Chapel ceiling]] composition, and his serious attention to perspective and shadowing <ref name=\":1\" />. \n\nThe first, is a ''[https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details/collection_image_gallery.aspx?assetId=6632001&objectId=671387&partId=1 Scheme for the Decoration of the Vault of the Sistine Chapel: Studies of Arms and Hands]''.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=671387&page=1&partId=1&peoA=114829-2-9&people=114829|title=drawing|website=British Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> The right side of the page was sketched in 1508 with black chalk, and is a study of [[Adam|Adam\u2019s]] limp hand, before it is ignited with the gift of life from [[God]], in the Creation of Adam scene. Michelangelo sketched this over a previous brown, lead point [[stylus]] study of the vaulted [[Sistine Chapel ceiling]]<ref name=\":2\" />. The entire composition is 274 millimeters in height and 386 millimeters in width<ref name=\":2\" />. The second sketch is titled ''[https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details/collection_image_gallery.aspx?assetId=200159001&objectId=716122&partId=1 Studies of a Reclining Male Nude: Adam in the Fresco \u2018The Creation of Man.\u2019]'' It was created in 1511 in dark red chalk, over a stylus under drawing.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?images=true&museumno=1926,1009.1&objectId=716122&page=1&partId=1|title=drawing|website=British Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Red chalk was Michelangelo\u2019s preferred medium at this period of time, as it could be shaved to a finer point than black chalk. Michelangelo used this fine point to create a scintillating skin surface, that was unique for this particular sketch, and is not seen in his later works<ref name=\":1\" />. The recto drawing is 193 millimeters in height and 259 millimeters in width<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\n=== Studies of a Reclining Male Nude: Adam in the Fresco 'The Creation of Man' ===\nIn the ''[https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details/collection_image_gallery.aspx?assetId=200159001&objectId=716122&partId=1 Studies of a Reclining Male Nude: Adam in the Fresco \u2018The Creation of Man]'', Adam is resting on earth, propped up by his forearm, with his thighs spread out and his torso slightly twisted to the side<ref name=\":3\" />. Michelangelo employed a male model to capture this effortful pose and used his red chalk to develop thick contours, in order to establish a definitive form, so every [[Sistine Chapel|chapel]] visitor could clearly recognize the muscular body from standing on the floor, 68 feet below the [[Sistine Chapel ceiling|ceiling]]<ref name=\":3\" />. \n\nIn Michelangelo\u2019s final fresco on the [[Sistine Chapel ceiling|ceiling]], Adam is physically beautiful, but spiritually still incomplete.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barolsky|first=Paul|date=2001|journal=Source: Notes in the History of Art|volume=20|issue=4|pages=6\u20138|issn=0737-4453|jstor=23206730|title=The Imperfection of Michelangelo's Adam|doi=10.1086/sou.20.4.23206730}}</ref> The sketch prefaces this story, as it is also incomplete in the sense that the only complete component of the drawing is Adam\u2019s twisted torso. Adam\u2019s other limbs bleed off of the trimmed page in immature form<ref name=\":1\" />. However, the work is not \u201cunfinished,\u201d as it reached its purpose for Michelangelo, which was to work out the details of the torso in the medium of chalk, so he was confident in the composition when he began the actual, permanent [[fresco]] panel.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.michelangelo.net/|title=Michelangelo Paintings, Sculptures & Artwork|website=www.michelangelo.net|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n==== Context ====\nMichelangelo heavily studied the human body and dissected numerous [[Cadaver|cadavers]] in his artistic career, and overtime became captivated by the male torso<ref name=\":4\" />. In his [[De pictura|treatises on painting and sculpture]], [[Leon Battista Alberti]], defined the male figure as a \"geometrical and harmonious sum of its parts<ref name=\":1\" />.\" Michelangelo however, felt that the torso was the powerhouse of the male body, and therefore warranted significant attention and mass in his art pieces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hekint.org/2018/04/11/anatomy-michelangelo-1475-1564/|title=The Anatomy of Michelangelo (1475-1564) - Hektoen International|website=hekint.org|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Thus, the torso in the ''Study'' represents an idealization of the male form, \u201csymbolic of the perfection of God\u2019s creation before [[Fall of man|the fall]]<ref name=\":3\" />.\"\n\n==== Sources ====\nMichelangelo\u2019s inspiration for the torso in the [https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details/collection_image_gallery.aspx?assetId=200159001&objectId=716122&partId=1 ''Studies of a Reclining Male Nude: Adam in the Fresco \u2018The Creation of Man''] sketch, is believed to be the [[Belvedere Torso]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/exhibitions/the-vaticans-belvedere-torso-british-museum-216945|title=The Vatican's Belvedere Torso Heads to London|date=2015-01-08|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> The [[Belvedere Torso]] is a fragmentary [[Marble sculpture|marble statue]] that is a 1<sup>st</sup> century BC Roman copy of an ancient Greek sculpture. Michelangelo historically used ancient, classical statuary as inspiration for the human physique in his great masterpieces<ref name=\":5\" />. In 2015, the [[Belvedere Torso]] was displayed with Michelangelo\u2019s sketch in the \u201cDefining Beauty: The Body in Ancient Greek Art\u201d show at the [[British Museum|British Museum in London]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/defining-beauty-the-body-in-ancient-greek-art-at-the-british-museum-gives-visitors-quite-an-eyeful-10123257.html|title=The British Museum's new exhibition on the body in Ancient Greek art gives visitors an eyeful|date=2015-03-21|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Fair as the young men of the [[Elgin marbles]], the Adam of the Sistine Chapel is unlike them in a total absence of that balance and completeness which express so well the sentiment of a self-contained, independent life. In that languid figure there is something rude and [[satyr]]-like, something akin to the rugged hillside on which it lies. His whole form is gathered into an expression of mere expectation and reception; he has hardly strength enough to lift his finger to touch the finger of the creator; yet a touch of the finger-tips will suffice.|author=[[Walter Pater]]|title=''The Renaissance: Studies in Art and Poetry''|source=\"The Poetry of Michelangelo\"}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n*{{slink|Apophatic theology#Western Christianity}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category inline|Sistine Chapel ceiling - Creation of Adam|Sistine Chapel ceiling - ''Creation of Adam''}}\n* [http://www.michelangelomodels.com Models of wax and clay used by Michelangelo in making his sculpture and paintings]\n\n{{Sistine Chapel}}\n{{Michelangelo}}\n{{Adam and Eve}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Creation Of Adam}}\n[[Category:1512 paintings]]\n[[Category:Paintings depicting Adam and Eve]]\n[[Category:Paintings of gods]]\n[[Category:Sistine Chapel ceiling]]\n", "name_user": "142.160.173.87", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePortrayal of the human brain)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Creation_of_Adam"}
